WOULD NOTIFY STATE AND LOCAL AUTHORITIES.

DRIVER PICKED UP THE LOAD IN MEMPHIS, TN.  THERE WERE TWO PICK-UPS. DRIVER SELPT IN KINGSVILLE, OH.  AT THE FUEL STOP.  AFTER AWAKENING, HE DID HIS PRE-TRIP AND FOUND THE SEEPAGE.  DRIVER CALLED SAFETY DEPT. DIRECTOR AND GAVE DETAILS, INCLUDING THE COLOR OF THE SEEPAGE.  SINCE THERE WERE TWO PICK-UPS, ONE WAS HAZARDUS AND THE LAST PICK-UP WAS NOT HAZARDOUS, THE DETERMINING FACTOR WAS (COLOR).  AFTER DRIVER CONFIRMED THE GOLDISH COLOR, SAFETY DIRECTOR FOUR R&D CALLED THE MANUFACTURER AND TALKED TO THE CHEMIST.  IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE PRODUCT WAS FROM THE FIRST PICK-UP AND WAS HAZARDOUS,  POISONOUS, AND HAS AN INHALING FACTOR AND EYE IRRITANT.  SAFETY DIRECTOR CALLED RESPONSE INVESTIGATOR WITH CRAWFORD AND COMPANY.  THEY LEFT FOR THE SIT (APPROX) 75 MILES AND WAS MET BY THE RESPONSE TEAM.  RESPONSE TEAM, INCLUDING THE KINGSVILLE FIRE DEPT. CLEANED UP AND CONTAINED SPILLAGE AND PUT LEAKING DRUM IN A "RECOVERY DRUM". DRIVER WAS HELD TILL ABOUT 9 AM THE NEXT DAY TO MAKE SURE THAT NOTHING ELSE WOULD LEAK FROM THE TRAILER.

ON JUNE 6,1995, OUR DRIVER PICKED UP FOUR(4) 55 GALLON DRUMS OF POISONOUS LIUQID, NOS 6.1 UN2810 PG III AT DELTA RESIN REFACTORIES, INC.  DRIVER BLOCKED AND BRACED DRUMS IN TRAILER (STRAIGHT TRUCK) AND PUT PLACARDS ON VEHICLE.  DRIVER CONTINUED TO NEXT PICK UP, BACKED INTO DOCK, SPOKE WITH KEUHN RUBBERS WAREHOUSE MAN, ADVISED HIM OF THE (4) DRUMS OF HAZARDOUS MATERIAL ON HIS TRUCK, AND TO BE CAREFUL WHEN LOADING FREIGHT WITH FORKLIFT.  THE WAREHOUSE PERSON HAD PROBLEMS WITH THE MASTER CYLINDER ON THE FORKLIFT, WHEN HE PUT JEEP INTO REVERSE THE JEEP WENT FORWARD AND PUNCTURED THE DRUM ABOUT 3 TO 5 INCHES FROM BOTTOM OF DRUM.  OUR DRIVER GOT HIS BILLS FROM TRUCK, CALLED 800 NUMBER ON BILLS, AND FOLLOWED PROCEDURES EXPLAINED BY DELTA RESIN AND MSDS SHEETS AND ERG #55 ALONG WITH HAZMAT TEAM AT KUEHN RUBBER.  FIRST, THE DRUM WAS TURNED TO AN UPRIGHT POSITION TO STOP LEAK, A PATCH KIT WAS USED TO SEAL DRUM.  HAZMAT RESPIRATORS WERE USED BECAUSE OF FUMES.  SPILL WAS SECURED WITH 6 - 4" BY 48" BERMS, AND OIL DRI.  ALL MATERIALS WERE DISPOSED OF IN AN OVERPACK CONTAINER AND TAKEN CARE OF BY HAZ MAT DISPOSAL COMPANY KEUHN RUBBER IS CONTRACTED WITH.  TRAILER AREA WAS WASHED DOWN AND DOOR VENTED FOR AIR CIRCULATION.

column168: TRAIN CREW ADDING UP INTERCHANGE CARS TO THEIR TRAIN FOUND SMALL LEAK AT BOTTOM OUTLET. ATSF AND CONTRACT RESPONDER ASSESSED THE CAR AND DETERMINED THAT LEAK WAS FROM PIPING ON THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE. THIS CAR HAS A SECONDARY OUTLET VALVE APPLIED TO THE CAP OF THE OUTLET PIPE. THE RELEASE WAS BETWEEN THE DISCHARGE FROM THE TOP OPERATED BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE AND THE SECONDARY VALVE AT A PIPE FITTING. THE LEAKING CONDITION WAS CORRECTED BY: (1) TIGHTENING THE TOP OPERATED BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE HANDLE 1/2 TURN; (2) TIGHTENING THE SECONDARY VALVE PIPING 1 TURN AND APPLYING EPOXY SEALER TO THE JOINT. MINIMAL PRODUCT SPILLAGE RECOVERED FOR DISPOSAL ALONG WITH MOST OF PRODUCT CAPTURED IN PLASTIC PAIL.

column168: THESE DRUMS WERE NOT LEAKING WHEN LOADED ONTO PEDDLE UNIT; HOWEVER DELIVERED DRIVER DID NOTE THAT THEY WERE DENTED.  AS HE WAS LEAVING ONE STOP, HE HAD TO MAKE AN EMERGENCY BRAKE STOP TO AVOID HITTING A CAR THAT WAS IN HIS BLIND SPOT ON HIS FIRST LOOK.  HE WAS ONLY TRAVELING 10 MPH, BUT IT WAS ENOUGH TO SHIFT ADJACENT FREIGHT IN HIS TRAILER INTO THIS DRUMS & THE ADJACENT FREIGHT HIT THE DRUM IN IT'S WEAKENED AREA RESULTING IN A SMALL CRACK IN THE FIRST RUNG FROM THE BOTTOM.  WHEN DRIVER MADE HIS NEXT STOP, HE COULD SMELL THAT HE HAD SPRUNG A LEAK.  HE PUT THE DRUM ON ITS SIDE ON A PALLET & TRIED TO PLUG THE HOLE WITH A SCREW UNTIL HE COULD GET BACK TO THE TERMINAL.  HE DID NOT LOSE MORE THAN A QUART OF MATERIAL. THERE WAS NO PROPER BLOCKING OR BRACING OF THESE DRUMS ON THE PEDDLE UNIT EITHER.  TERMINAL MANAGER WILL ADDRESS WHOEVER LOADED THIS UNIT TO AVOID FUTURE INSTANCES OF THIS NATURE.

column17: HUNT J B SPECIAL COMMODITIES I
column168: DRIVER ARRIVED AT THE RECEIVER TO FIND ONE DRUM LEAKING. THE DRUM WAS OFF-LOADED AND THE SPILLED MATERIAL WAS CLEANED FROM THE TRAILER. CAUSE OF THE SPILL APPEARED TO BE FROM A HOLE IN THE TOP EDGE OF THE DRUM (LID AREA). ALL WASTE WAS ACCEPTED BY THE RECEIVER.

UPON INSPECTING THE UNIT THE DRIVER FOUND SUBSTANCE BEGINNING TO LEAK FROM THE RIGHT REAR OF THE TRAILER. DRIVER IMMEDIATELY USED A HAZARDOUS MATERIALS CONTAINMENT PACKAGE AND A 25 GALLON PAIL FOR MATERIAL TO SPILL INTO. ONCE THE PRODUCT  STOPPED LEAKING, THE DRIVER RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER AND UPON UNLOADING AND INSPECTION, IT WAS FOUND THAT THE PALLET IN WHICH THE PRODUCT WAS LOADED ON WAS DEFECTIVE. THE PALLET SLATS HAD GAPS BETWEEN THEM OF OVER AN INCH ALLOWING THE PAILS TO SHIFT SIDEWAYS AND INTO OPENINGS BETWEEN THE SLATS. ALSO THE PAILS WERE SUPPOSED TO BE WRAPPED AT THE BOTTOM WITH A CORRUGATED CARTON APPROXIMATELY SIX INCHES HIGH TO CONTAIN AND PROTECT THE BOTTOM LAYER OF PAILS FROM SHIFTING. THE PALLET OF PAILS WERE SHRINK WRAPPED. IN ADDITION, THE PALLET OF PAILS WERE SUPPOSED TO BE LOADED ADJACENT TO A PALLET OF CARTON FREIGHT FOR PROTECTION IN CASE OF SHIFTING DURING TRANSIT. THE PALLET IN QUESTION WAS LOADED ADJACENT TO ANOTHER PALLET OF 5 GALLON PAILS. SHIPPER WILL INSTRUCT LOADER ON PROPOER LOADING PROCEDURES FOR THIS MATERIAL. NOTIFICATION WAS MADE TO CHEMTREC. SHIPPER DECONTAMINATED TRAILER.

WHILE TRAILER WAS BEING STRIPPED THE DOCK PERSON UNLOADING THE SHIPMENT HIT THE CARTON WITH THE FORKLIFT BLADE CAUSING THE DAMAGE TO THE CARTON. 1 CARTON CONTAINING 4-1 GALLON JUGS WAS HIT PUNCTURING ONE OF THE GALLON JUGS AND APPROXIMATELY 1/2 GALLON WAS LOST. ABSORBENT WAS PUT ON FLOOR OF THE DOCK TO ABSORB THE LEAK. THE MATERIAL WAS NEUTRALIZED AND THE REMAINING FREIGHT DELIVERED TO THE CONSIGNEE.

DISCOVERED 2 BAGS LEAKING ON REAR OF TRAILER WHILE UNLOADING AT THE DOCK. PLACED THE LEAKING BAGS INTO A RECOVERY PAIL AND FORWARDED THE SHIPMENT ON TO DESTINATION. CONSIGNEE ACCEPTED THE WHOLE SHIPMENT.

SHIPPER'S MECHANIC WAS REPAIRING A VALVE BY REPLACING A GASKET ON THEIR TANK. WHEN COMPLETING REPAIRS, THEY LEFT THE VALVE OPEN. WHEN LOADING WAS TO BEGIN AND THE VALVE WAS TURNED ON AT THEIR TANK THE PUMP NEVER CAME ON BUT GRAVITY PULLED PRODUCT OUT OF THE SPOUT AND ONTO TRANSPORT TRAILER AND GROUND. CUSTOMER PUT GROUND COKE (BREEZE) ON THE SPILLED AREA AND ASSUMED FULL RESPONSIBILITY FOR SPILL AND CLEAN UP,INCLUDING DISPOSAL.

DURING ROUTINE AIRCRAFT STOP, ODORS WERE EVIDENT AROUND THE PACKAGES. INSIDE PLASTIC BOTTLES WERE FOUND TO BE LOOSE ON SOME OF THE INNER BOTTLES.  IT APPEARS THAT THE SCREW ON CAPS WERE NOT SECURED BY "POSITIVE MEANS" AND REDUCED AIR PRESSURE CAUSED SOME OF THE CAPS TO BECOME LOOSE. THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED WHO WAS VERY CONCERED AND WORKED WITH THEIR PACKAGING ENGINEERS IN PROVIDING POSITIVE CLOSURE FOR FUTURE SHIPMENTS. THE FAA WAS ALSO NOTIFIED OF THE DISCREPANCY.

column168: DRIVER HAD JUST MADE A LEFT HAND TURN WHEN THE TRUCK WENT OFF THE EDGE OF THE ROAD.  DRIVER THEN ATTEMPTED TO BRING THE TRUCK BACK INTO THE ROAD WHEN THE MOMENTUM OF THE LIQUID AND THE SLOPING ROAD SIDE CAUSED THE TRUCK TO OVERTURN.  THE DRIVER THEN CALLED "911" AND THE LOCAL FIRE, POLICE AND A HAZARDOUS MATERIAL RESPONSE TEAM RESPONDED.  THE SPILLED LIQUID WAS PICKED UP AND THE SITE IS CURRENTLY BEING CLEANED UP.  THE REASON FOR THE TRUCK GOING OFF THE ROAD HAD NOT BEEN DETERMINED.  ALL DRIVER HAVE BEEN GIVENN A COPY OF A DOT NOTICE TITLES ON GUARD "WHICH TALKS ABOUT LIQUIDS SHIFTING AND CAUSING OVERTURNS"

THERE WAS SPILLAGE OF PRODUCT AND FERGUSON HARBOUR INC. IS THE COMPANY WHICH IS CONTRACTED TO CLEAN UP THE AREA CONTAMINATED BY THE SPILL. THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED AND DID NOT ENTER A NEAR BY CREEK.  THE DRIVER WAS TAKEN TO TYLER HOLMES HOSPITAL AND LATER TRANFERRED TO UNIVERSITY HOSPITAL IN JACKSONS, MS. column62: Fire, Temperature, or Heat; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: THERE WAS A HEAD-ON COLLISION ENGULFING THE TRACTOR/TRAILER/CARGO IN FIRE. THE CARGO CONSISTED OF: (A) PAPER CUPS, (B) AEROSOL PAINT (NON-HAZARDOUS), (C) CONSUMER PESTICIDES (NON-HAZARDOUS), AND (D) CLEANING COMPOUNDS [NA1993-CONTAING XYLENE AND ISOPROPYL ALCOHOL].  THE EQUIPMENT AND CARGO WERE ALLOWED TO BURN FROM APPROXIMATELY 0300 UNTIL 1245 WHEN THE UNIT WAS FOAMED.  THE INTENSE HEAT OF THE FIRE INCINERATED THE CARGO, BURNING HAZARDOUS MATERIALS AND TOXICS.  THE ONLY HAZARDOUS CONSTITUENT OF THE CARGO DETECTED AS BEING RELEASED TO THE ENVIRONMENT WAS A TRACE AMOUNT OF XYLENE IN THE SOIL ON THE SHOULDER OF THE HIGHWAY IN THE IMMEDIATE VICINITY OF THE ACCIDENT.  THE PRIMARY ENVIRONMENTAL RELEASE WAS DIESEL FUEL FROM THE RUPTURED FUEL TANK.  IT IS THOUGH THAT THE DIESEL LEAKED IMMEDIATELY AFTER THE ACCIDENT AND THUS PRIOR TO THE FIRE CONSUMPTION. THE DIESEL RELEASE WAS CONFINED TO HIGHWAY PAVEMENT AND SOIL IMMEDIATELY ADJACENT TO THE HIGHWAY.  THERE WERE NO OTHER ENVIRONMENTAL IMPACTS; NO SENSITIVE RECEPTORS (i.e.) DRAINS, WATER WELLS, ETS.) WERE AFFECTED.  THE GA ENVIRONMENTAL PROTECTION DIVISION (GA EPD) WAS NOTIFIED.  GA EPD'S ON SITE REPRESENTATIVE WAS MS. ROBERTA RUNGE.  GA EPD CALLED IN THE USEPA FOR HAZARDOUS AND TOXIC TESTING CAPABILITY.  AIR TESTING PERFORMED BY USEPA PASSED AS NON-TOXIC.  AS MENTIONED EARLIER, ONLY TRACE AMOUNTS OF XYLENE WERE DETECTED BY USEPA IN THE SURFACE SOIL IMMEDIATELY ADJACENT TO THE HIGHWAY.  THERE WERE NO OTHER RELEASES OF HAZARDOUS OR TOXIC SUBSTANCES. GA ENVIRONMENTAL SPECIALIST, INC.  WAS RETAINED BY ESTES EXPRESS LINES AS THE ENVIRONMENTAL REMEDIATION CONTRACTOR.  THEY EXCAVATED 15 TO 20 TONS OF SOIL IN THE DIESEL IMPACTED AREA.  LID METER READING WERE WELL BELOW REGULATORY LIMITS.  THE EVACATION WAS BACKFILLED WITH SOIL PROVIDED BY THE GA DOT.  THE AEROSOL CANS WERE COLLLECTED AND BAGGED, AND SUBSEQUENTLY LANDFILLED AS NON-HAZARDOUS WASTE.  THE DIESEL CONTAMINATED SOIL IS BEING DISPOSED OF AS NON-HAZARDOUS WASTE PER ANALYTICAL TEST RESULT.

IT WAS DETERMINED THAT PRODUCT HAD LEAKED INTO THE HEATER COIL CONDENSATE LINES AND SUBSEQUENTLY LEAKED OUT THROUGH LOOSE ENDS CAPS. THE CONDENSATE LINE CAPS WERE TIGHTENED AND THE LEAK WAS STOPPED. column42: GASOLINE INCLUDES GASOLINE MIXED WITH ETHYL ALCOHOL, WITH NOT MORE THAN 10% ALCOHOL
column168: I WAS DISPATCHED TO CIRCLE K STORE #084 ON WEST BROADWAY IN IDAHO FALLS, ID. I ARRIVED THERE AT APPROXIMATELY 9:30 PM. THE ATTENDANT AND I MEASURED THE TANKS (NL & PREMIUM). I PRECEEDED TO HOOK UP TIGHT FILLS AND HOSES TOO BOTH TANKS AND THE TRAILER. THEN BEGAN DISPENSING BOTH PRODUCTS. I WAS ALONGSIDE THE TRUCK WHEN I COULD SEE GASOLINE STARTING TO COME OUT OF THE VAPOR RECOVERY HOLE ON THE PREMIUM TANK (THIS PARTICULAR HOLE IS DESIGNED TO BE PLUGGED AND NOT LEAK IN ANY WAY, APPARENTLY THERE WAS A MALFUNCTION THAT NEEDS TO BE CORRECTED BY THE STORE). I STEPPED TO THE TRAILER AND STOPPED THE FLOW OF GASOLINE. APPROXIMATELY 10 GALLONS ESCAPED. THE ATTENDANT SAW THE GAS ON THE GROUND, STEPPED OUT TO SURVEY THE SITUATION, THEN RETURNED TO THE STORE, CALLED THE MANAGER AND THE FIRE DEPARTMENT. THE FIRE DEPARTMENT ARRIVED IN A SHORT TIME AND BEGAN TO PUT OUT A CLAY BASE ABSORBENT. THE AREA WAS SECURED TO KEEP VEHICLES OUT OF THE AREA. THE FIRE CHIEF TOLD ME THAT BOWEN PETROLEUM WOULD HAVE TO CLEAN UP THE AREA. THE FIRE CHIEF WAS ABLE TO GET THE PHONE NUMBER OF THE BOWEN PETROLEUM DISPATCHER ON CALL IN IDAHO FALLS (SCOT HARRIS). I CALLED SCOT ON THE TELEPHONE, HE CAME OVER IMMEDIATELY AND THE TWO OF US SWEPT UP THE ABSORBENT AND PLACED IT INTO PLASTIC BAGS. WE THEN PUT THE BAGS INTO BOXES IN THE BACK OF HIS PICKUP. THE CLEAN UP WAS COMPLETED AND I LEFT AT 11:00 PM. THERE WERE TWO EQUIPMENT MALFUNCTIONS. 1) THE AUTO VALVE DID NOT FUNCTION PROPERLY, 2) THE VAPOR HOLE WAS NOT SEALED. AS NOTED EARLIER IN THIS STATEMENT, THE TIGHT FILL THE HOSE WAS HOOKED ON FUNCTIONED CORRECTLY. THE OVER FLOW WAS FROM THE VAPOR RECOVERY HOLE. THERE WAS A MALFUNCTION OF EQUIPMENT THAT CAUSED THE OVER FLOW. AS THE TANK FILLED TO CAPACITY INSTEAD OF THE FLOW BEING STOPPED AUTOMATICALLY BY THE "AUTO VALVE" AS IT WOULD IF THE EQUIPMENT WAS OPERATING CORRECTLY THE FLOW OF GASOLINE WOULD HAVE BACKED UP INTO THE TRAILER.

OUR CUSTOMER CANBERRA SUPPLIED OUR DRIVER WITH HAZORB MATERIAL (FLOOR DRY) TO SOAK UP THE PRODUCT. THE DRIVER THEN SWEPT THE HAZORB MATERIAL AND PUT IT INTO THE VANS RECOVERY DRUM. A VAN TRAILER CONTAINING HAZARDOUS WASTE WAS ENROUTE FROM QUALITY CHEMICALS INC. LOCATED AT INDUSTRIAL PARK IN TYRONE, PA TO CLEAN HARBORS OF CHICAGO, INC. LOCATED AT 11800 S STONEY ISLAND AVENUE CHICAGO, IL. DURING THE COURSE OF THE TRIP, THE DRIVER MADE A ROUTINE STOP IN ORDER TO CONDUCT A LOAD AND TIRE CHECK AND DISCOVERED THAT APPROXIMATELY 1 GALLON OF LIQUID HAD ESCAPED FROM THE BOTTOM OF ONE OF THE CONTAINERS ONTO THE FLOOR OF THE VAN TRAILER WHERE IT WAS PREVENTED FROM ESCAPING TO THE ENVIRONMENT. THE DRIVER IMMEDIATELY CONTACTED HIS DISPATCHER WHO DISPATCHED A CLEAN-UP CREW TO THE SCENE IN ORDER TO IDENTIFY THE CAUSE OF THE RELEASE AND TO INITIATE CORRECTIVE ACTIONS. UPON ARRIVAL AT THE SCENE, THE CLEAN-UP CREW INSPECTED THE LOAD AND DISCOVERED THAT RESIDUAL LIQUID THAT WAS NOT VISIBLE AT THE TIME OF LOADING SEPARATED FROM THE DEBRIS AND ESCAPED FROM THE CONTAINER. THE CREW THEN ABSORBED ALL FREE LIQUIDS WITH SPEEDI DRY AND REPACKAGED THE DAMAGED CONTAINERS ALONG WITH ALL CLEAN-UP DEBRIS FOR CONTINUING TRANSPORT TO THE WASTE MANAGEMENT FACILITY INDICATED ON THE ORIGINAL SHIPPING DOCUMENT. PRIOR TO DEPARTURE FROM THE SHIPPERS LOCATION, THE LOAD WAS INSPECTED AND NO EVIDENCE OF LEAKING OR DAMAGE WAS OBSERVED. ALL DRIVERS AND LOADING PERSONNEL WILL CONTINUE TO INSPECT EACH CONTAINER AS IT IS LOADED AND TAKE APPROPRIATE ACTIONS IN THE EVENT  A CONTAINER IS FOUND NOT TO BE PROPERLY CLOSED OR NOT STRUCTURALLY SOUND. IN ADDITION, THE SHIPPER HAS BEEN INSTRUCTED TO UTILIZE ALTERNATE CONTAINERS FOR MATERIALS THAT COULD CONTAIN RESIDUAL LIQUIDS NOT VISIBLE AT THE TIME OF LOADING BUT WHICH COULD PHASE OUT DURING THE NORMAL COURSE OF TRANSPORTATION.

A VAN TRAILER CONTAINING HAZARDOUS WASTE WAS ENROUTE FROM QUALITY CHEMICALS, INC. LOCATED AT INDUSTRIAL PARK IN TYTONE, PA TO CLEAN HARBORS OF CHICAGO INC. LOCATED AT 11800 S STONEY ISLAND AVENUE IN CHICAGO IL. DURING THE COURSE OF THE TRIP THE DRIVER MADE A ROUTINE STOP IN ORDER TO CONDUCT A LOAD AND TIRE CHECK AND DISCOVERED THAT APPROXIMATELY 1 PINT OF LIQUID HAD ESCAPED FROM THE VAN TRAILER ONTO ASPHALT PAVEMENT. THE DRIVER IMMEDIATELY CONTAINED THE RELEASE USING POLYETHYLENE SHEETING AND SPREAD SPEEDI DRY ON THE FREE LIQUID. HE THEN CONTACTED HIS DISPATCHER WHO DISPATCHED A CLEAN-UP CREW TO THE SCENE IN ORDER TO IDENTIFY THE CAUSE OF THE RELEASE AND TO INITIATE CORRECTIVE ACTIONS. UPON ARRIVAL AT THE SCENE, THE CLEAN-UP CREW INSPECTED THE LOAD AND DISCOVERED THAT THE LOAD HAD SHIFTED CAUSING TWO OF THE CONTAINERS TO SLIDE ONTO THE CORNER OF THE PALLET THEY WERE RESTING ON AND TEAR A HOLE IN THE SIDE OF THE CONTAINER. IT WAS ALSO DISCOVERED THAT APPROXIMATELY 2 GALLONS OF MATERIAL WAS RELEASED TO THE FLOOR OF THE VAN TRAILER AND OF THIS, APPROXIMIATELY 1 PINT ESCAPED TO THE ASPHALT PAVEMENT. THE CREW THEN ABSORBED ALL FREE LIQUIDS WITH SPEEDI DRY AND REPACKAGED THE DAMAGED CONTAINERS ALONG WITH ALL CLEAN-UP DEBRIS FOR CONTINUING TRANSPORT TO THE WASTE MANAGEMENT FACILITY INDICATED ON THE ORIGINAL SHIPPING DOCUMENT. PRIOR TO DEPARTURE FROM THE SHIPPER'S LOCATION, THE LOAD WAS INSPECTED AND NO EVIDENCE OF LEAKING OR DAMAGE WAS OBSERVED. IN ADDITION, THE BLOCKING AND BRACING UTILIZED WAS SECURE AT THE TIME OF DISPATCH. ALL DRIVERS AND LOADING PERSONNEL WILL CONTINUE TO INSPECT EACH CONTAINER AS IT IS LOADED AND TAKE APPROPRIATE ACTIONS IN THE EVENT A CONTAINER IS FOUND NOT TO BE PROPERLY CLOSED OR NOT STRUCTURALLY SOUND. DRIVERS WILL ALSO CONTINUE TO INSPECT THE COMPLETED LOAD TO INSURE THAT ADEQUATE BLOCKING AND BRACING IS UTILIZED. FINALLY, THE SHIPPER HAS BEEN INSTRUCTED TO UTILIZE ALTERNATE CONTAINERS FOR MATERIALS THAT COULD CONTAIN RESIDUAL LIQUIDS NOT VISIBLE AT THE TIME OF LOADING BUT WHICH COULD PHASE OUT DURING THE NORMAL COURSE OF TRANSPORTATION.

A DRUM WAS KNOCKED OVER AND APPROXIMATELY 1 GALLON SPILLED ONTO THE TRAILER FLOOR.  ABSORBENT WAS USED TO CLEAN UP THE LIQUID AND THEN PACKAGED FOR DISPOSAL.  THE OPERATIONS MANAGER HELD A SAFETY MEETING TO DISCUSS THE PROPER PROCEDURES FOR HANDLING DRUMS.

THE INCIDENT OCCURRED AS THE DRUMS WERE BEING LOADED INTO THE REAR OF THE TRAILER.  THREE DRUMS OF THE PHOSPHORIC ACID SOLUTION WERE PLACED ON THE REAR OF THE TRAILER BY A FORKLIFT DRIVEN BY AN EG&G EMPLOYEE.  AS THE LAIDLAW DRIVER WAS REMOVING THE DRUMS FROM THE PALLET, HE LOST HIS GRIP ON ONE OF THE DRUMS AND IT FELL ONTO THE FLOOR OF THE TRAILER.  THE TOP OF THE DOT 34 POLY DRUM SPLIT UPON IMPACT WITH THE TRAILER FLOOR, SPILLING ABOUT FIFTEEN GALLONS OF MATERIAL.  THE SPILL WAS THE RESULT OF THE CONTAINER FAILURE BY THE DOT 34 POLY DRUM.  AS A PRECAUTION, THE OTHER TWO DOT 34 POLY DRUMS OF THE SAME MATERIAL SHIPPED ON THAT MANIFEST LINE WERE PLACED IN POLY OVERPACKES AT LAIDLAW ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES (TS), INC. DUE TO THEIR BRITTLE APPEARANCE.  THE LAIDLAW DRIVER, WITH THE HELP OF EG&G PERSONNEL, RIGHTED THE DRUM, PREVENTING FURTHER SPILLAGE.  APPROXIMATELY HALF THE SPILLED MATERIAL REMAINED IN THE TRAILER, WHILE THE OTHER PORTION WAS SPILLED ON THE CEMENT PAD AT THE REAR OF THE VEHICLE.  IMMEDIATE ACTION WAS TAKEN TO CONTAIN AND CLEAN UP THE SPILLAGE.  THE SPILLED MATERIAL WAS NEUTRALIZED WITH SODIUM BICARBONATE AND OIL DRY.  ALL LIQUIDS IN BOTH THE TRAILER AND ON THE CEMENT PAD WERE ABSORBED AND COLLECTED IN THIS MANNER.  THE DAMAGED CONTAINER WAS PLACED IN A POLY EIGHTY-FIVE GALLON OVERPACK CONTAINER, INTO WHICH WAS ALSO PLACED THE MATERIAL FROM THE SPILL CLEANUP OPERATION.  ALL MATERIALS WERE SHIPPED TO LAIDLAW ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES (TS), INC. IN CLEARWATER, FLORIDA.  DISPOSAL WILL BE MADE IN ACCORDANCE WITH LOCAL, STATE, AND FEDERAL REGULATIONS.

CSXT'S TRAINMASTER AT BIRMINGHAM, AL., REPORTED A TANK CAR GOT HELD UP ON THE HUMP RETARDER & ANOTHER CAR WAS RELEASED INTO IT.  WHEN THE TANK CAR WAS STRUCK, IT RELEASED A CLOUD OF VAPORS FROM THE TOP.  THE CAR WAS INSPECTED, NO LIQUID LEAKAGE WAS FOUND; SUSPECT SAFETY RELIEF VALVE FUNCTIONED.  THERE WAS NO DAMAGE TO THE CAR.  THE CAR WAS MOVED & NO LIQUID LEAKAGE WAS DETECTED.  THE CAR WAS THEN RELEASED TO CONTINUE TO DESTINATION.  THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED VIA CHEMTEC.

CSXT'S TRAINMASTER AT CHATTANOOGA, TN., REPORTED THAT A MAINTENANCE AWAY CREW HAD SMELLED A STRONG ODOR COMING FROM AROUND A TANK CAR IN THE YARD. THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED VIA CHEMTREC.  THE SHIPPER ADVISED PRODUCT HAS LOW ODOR THRESHOLD.  CSXT HAZMAT CALLED LOCAL RESPONSE CO. TO INSPECT THE CAR.  THE CONTRACTOR FOUND THE ONE INCH AIR LINE VALVE WAS SLIGHTLY OPEN & THE VALVE PLUG WAS LOOSE.  THEY ALSO FOUND ONE MANWAY SECUREMENT BOLT WAS NOT TORQUED DOWN TIGHT.  THE CONTRACTOR CLOSED THE AIR LINE VALVE, TIGHTENED THE PLUG & TIGHTENED DOWN THE MANWAY BOLT.  THE ODOR STOPPED AND THE CAR WAS RELEASED.

DURING ROUTINE TIRE INSPECTION, THE DRIVER THOUGHT HE NOTICED AN ODOR EMINATING FROM THE TRAILER.  A CLOSER CHECK OF THE LOAD REVEALED NOTHING. LATER THE NEXT DAY THE DRIVER AGAIN THOUGHT HE NOTICED AN ODOR AND AGAIN NO PROBLEM WAS VISABLE DURING A LOAD CHECK.  THE FLOOR, PALLETS AND OTHER FREIGHT WERE NOT FOUND TO BE WET OR JEOPARDIZED IN ANY WAY.  AT THE DELIVERY POINT WHEN THE FREIGHT WAS BEING BROKEN DOWN FROM THE PALLETS AN EMPTY STEEL CAN WAS FOUND.  FURTHER INSPECTION REVEALED A MINUTE CRACK IN THE BOTTOM OF THE CAN.  DISPOSAL WAS PERFORMED BY FISHER SCI PERSONNEL.

column168: OUR TRUCK & TRAILER WERE TRAVELING IN THE #1 LANE OF THE 15 FWY NORTH BOUND, WHEN ACCORDING TO THE DRIVER THE TRAILER GOT INTO THE CURB AREA CAUSING THE TRAILER TO START TO WANDER SIDE TO SIDE.  DRIVER ATTEMPTED TO GET UNIT IN CONTROL, WHEN TRAILER TURNED OVER ON IT'S LEFT SIDE IN THE #3 LANE OF THE I 5 NORTH BOUND FWY.  THE TRAILER THEN BEGAN TO SLIDE, BRINGING THE REAR OF THE TRUCK AROUND, AS THIS OCCURRED THE TANK TRUCK WAS STEERED TO THE RIGHT.  WHEN IT GOT TO THE MEDIAN WHICH SEPARATED THE I 5 AND I 10 NORTH TRANSITION THE REAR OF THE TANK TRUCK WAS PULLED AROUND 180 DEGREES. THE TRAILER THEN SLID ACROSS THE MEDIAN MAKING CONTACT WITH THE BARRACADE TO THE TRAIN OVERCROSSING.  AT THIS TIME THE TANK STRUCK THE ANCHORING POST FOR THE CABLES WHICH HOLDS THE CABLES TO THE BARRACADE, THIS CUT THE TRAILER TANK OPEN AND ROLLED IT ONE MORE TIME 180 DEGREES COMING TO REST ON ITS RIGHT SIDE.  WITH THE RELEASE OF GASOLINE THE TRAILER CAUGHT FIRE, THE FIRE TRAVELED UNDER THE TRUCK TANK AND CAUGHT THIS ON FIRE.  NO DAMAGE HAD OCCURRED TO THE TANK TRUCK PRIOR TO THE FIRE. BURNING GASOLINE THEN ENTERED THE DRAIN OFF SYSTEMS FOR THE FWY AND WAS CONTAINED TO THE PUMP HOUSE CATCH BASIN WHICH WAS APPROXIMATELY 300 YARDS SOUTH OF THE ACCIDENT, AT HUMBOLT & 23RD.  RECOMMENDATIONS WOULD BE GIVE MORE ROOM IN #1 LANE BETWEEN THE WHITE LINE AND THE CURBS, THIS AREA IS BAD DUE TO THE INCREASED NUMBER OF LANES PUT IN ON THIS THE NEWER TYPE OF BARRACADE SUCH AS THE YELLOW TUBS WITH SAND, IF THIS WAS THERE I FEEL IMPACT THE NEWER TYPE OF BARRACADE SUCH AS THE YELLOW TUBS WITH SAND, IF THIS WAS THERE I FEEL THE TANK WOULD NOT HAVE BEEN RUPTURED. NO PRODUCT WAS LOST TILL IT HIT THE BARRACADE.

column168: AT APPROX. 1245 HRS ON 6/13/95, RAILROAD TANK CAR PPGX 3248 WAS FOUND TO BE LEAKING FROM A RUPTURED RELIEF DISK. DURING THE PROCESS OF ISOLATING THE CAR A FEW DROPS OF THE MATERIAL SPLASHED ON THE KCS CONDUCTOR. HE WAS IMMEDIATELY FLUSHED WITH WATER AND TRANSPORTED TO AREA DOCTOR. THERE WERE NO RESULTING INJURIES, HOWEVER, THE CONDUCTOR WAS GIVEN A PRECAUTIONARY TETNUS INJECTION AND RELEASED BACK TO WORK. (NOTE; NOT  FRA REPORTABLE INJURY.) ALL CONCERNED WERE NOTIFIED, CHEMTREC #36375. THE CAR WAS REPAIRED BY ARIZONA CHEMICAL AND THE CAR WAS RELEASED BACK INTO SERVICE.

column168: LIDON TOTE WAS NOT PROPERLY SECURED. PRODUCT SPLASH OUT ONTO FLOOR OF TRAILER. DIVERSEY CORP SENT NEW TOTE TO CLEAN UP CREW PUMPED OVER INTO NEW TOTE. OLD TOTE SENT BACK TO SHIPPER. PRODUCT SENT ON TO CONSIGNEE.

THE DRUMS WERE NOT LEAKING WHEN LOADED ONTO PEDDLE UNIT; HOWEVER DELIVERING DRIVER DID NOTE THAT THEY WERE DENTED. AS HE WAS LEAVING ONE STOP, HE HAD TO MAKE AN EMERGENCY BRAKE STOP TO AVOID HITTING A CAR THAT WAS IN HIS BLIND SPOT ON HIS FIRST LOOK. HE WAS ONLY TRAVELING 10 MPH, BUT IT WAS ENOUGH TO SHIFT ADJACENT FREIGHT IN HIS TRAILER INTO THIS DRUM AND THE ADJACENT FRT HIT THE DRUM IN ITS WEAKENED AREA RESULTING IN A SMALL CRACK IN THE FIRST RUNG FROM THE BOTTOM. WHEN DRIVER MADE HIS NEXT STOP, HE COULD SMELL THAT HE HAD SPRUNG A LEAK. HE PUT THE DRUM ON ITS SIDE ON A PALLET & TRIED TO PLUG THE HOLE WITH A SCREW UNTIL HE COULD GET BACK TO THE TERMINAL. HE DID NOT LOSE MORE THAN A QUART OF MATERIAL THERE WAS NO PROPER BLOCKING OR BRACING OF THESE DRUMS ON THE PEDDLE UNIT EITHER. TERMINAL MANAGER WILL ADDRESS WHOEVER LOADED THIS UNIT TO AVOID FUTURE INSTANCES OF THIS NATURE.
LOADER WAS MOVING A SKID WITH A FORKLIFT AND HIT THE DRUM WITH A PROTRUDING BLADE.

DRIVER STATES LOAD SHIFTED EN ROUTE TO CUSTOMER, CAUSING 5 GALLON CONTAINERS TO FALL ON THE FLOOR OF THE TRAILER. OVERTURNED CONTAINERS WERE RIGHTED, INSPECTED AND FOUND TO HAVE NO VISIBLE DAMAGE. IMPACT OF CONTAINER ON FLOOR SEEMS TO HAVE FORCE SOME OF PRODUCT PAST CLOSURE IN AMOUNT OF APPROXIMATELY 1 QUART. DRIVER CLEANED UP SPILLED PRODUCT WITH SODA ASH. RECOMMENDATIONS TO PREVENT FUTURE INCIDENTS: 1) DRIVERS AND LOADERS TO BE RETRAINED IN PROPER LOADING AND BLOCKING TECHNIQUES, AND REFRESHED ABOUT DRIVING TECHNIQUES TO MINIMIZE LOAD SHIFT. 2) EMPLOYEES FILLING CONTAINERS TO BE RETRAINED IN PROPER CONTAINER CLOSURE AND PALLETIZING.
WHILE UNLOADING, DAMAGED CONTAINER WAS DISCOVERED. APPARENTLY DAMAGED WHILE IN TRANSIT DUE TO IMPROPER LOADING. PROPER LOADING TECHNIQUES SHOULD BE IMPLEMENTED ON FUTURE SHIPMENTS.

column168: DOCK MAN DISCOVERED LEAKING DRUM AS HE WAS UNLOADING TRAILER. THE DRUM HAD A DEFECTIVE SEAM NEAR THE BOTTOM WHICH ALLOWED FOR A SMALL LEAKAGE. DRUM TRANSFERRED TO OS&D FOR FURTHER HANDLING. SHIPPERS SHOULD ENSURE THAT DRUMS ARE TRAVEL-WORTHY BEFORE SHIPPING PRODUCT.

THE CARTON HAD ALREADY BEEN LOADED ON TOP OF A SKID OF FREIGHT ON AN OUTBOUND TRAILER AT THE DOCK. THE DOCK MAN REMOVED THE CARTON FROM THE TOP OF THE SKID OF FREIGHT AND PLACED IT ON THE CONCRETE FLOOR OF THE DOCK. THE IMPACT OF THE GLASS JUGS INSIDE THE CARTON WITH THE CONCRETE FLOOR CAUSED ONE OF THE JUGS TO SHATTER RELEASING THE CONTENTS. INCIDENT REPORTED TO THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER TO MR. CARROLL WITH REPORT #294402 ISSUED. CARTON TRANSFERRED TO OS&D FOR FURTHER HANDLING. THE DOCK MAN WAS CAUTIONED TO USE MORE CARE WHEN HANDLING CARTONS WITH GLASS CONTAINERS. RECOMMEND THAT THE BOTTOM OF CARTONS CONTAIN A STYROFOAM INSERT SO AS TO REDUCE THE LIKELIHOOD OF FUTURE DAMAGES.

THE TOTE BIN WAS BEING UNLOADED OFF OF THE CITY UNTIL WHEN SUDDENLY THE BIN SLIDE OFF THE FORKS AND FELL ON ITS SIDE. THE LID ON THE BIN OPENED AND THE CONTENTS BEGAN TO SPILL. APPROXIMATELY 100 GALLONS POURED OUT BEFORE THE BIN WAS ABLE TO BE STOOD UPRIGHT.
DOCK HAND UNLOADING STRUCK DRUM WITH FORKLIFT BLADE. EXTRA CAUTION SHOULD BE USED WHEN UNLOADING WITH FORKLIFT.

THE CARTON HAD BEEN PLACED ON TOP OF A SKID OF FREIGHT IN THE NOSE OF AN OUTBOUND TRAILER. THE CARTON WAS RIGHT ON THE EDGE OF THE SKID OF FREIGHT. ANOTHER SKID HAD BEEN LOADED BEHIND THE SKID OF FREIGHT WITH THE HAZARDOUS CARTON. THE DOCK MAN PULLED THE BACK SKID OFF TO REARRANGE SOME FREIGHT. WHEN THE SKID WAS PULLED BACK THE CARTON FELL OFF THE OTHER SKID AND HIT THE TRAILER FLOOR. THE IMPACT CAUSED TWO OF THE GLASS JUGS TO SHATTER THEREBY RELEASING THEIR CONTENTS. CARTON TRANSFERRED TO OS&D FOR FURTHER HANDLING. THE HAZARDOUS CARTON SHOULD NEVER HAVE BEEN LOADED ON TOP OF A SKID OF FREIGHT WITH THE CHANCE OF IT FALLING OFF. THE CARTON SHOULD HAVE BEEN LOADED ON THE TRAILER FLOOR. THIS WAS EXPLAINED TO THE DOCK MAN TO PREVENT FUTURE INCIDENTS.

BEGAN WITH LOAD AT 815. AT APPROXIMATELY 1030 AL BRYANT WAS UNLOADING THIS SHIPMENT. IT WAS FOUND TO BE LEAKING WHEN IT CAME OUT OF TRAILER. NO EVIDENCE OF LEAKING PRIOR TO UNLOADING. OTHERS WERE BOX DAMAGE AND 1 GALLON JUG WAS MASHED BUT NOT LEAKING.

A CARGO TANK CONTAINING HAZARDOUS WASTE WAS ENROUTE FROM CLEAN HARBORS OF BRAINTREE, INC LOCATED AT 385 QUINCY AVE IN BRAINTREE, MA TO CONSOLIDATED RAIL CAR FOR CONTINUING TRANSPORTATION. UPON ARRIVAL AT THE RAIL YARD, THE LIQUID LEVEL GAGE LOCATED ON THE REAR OF THE TANK TRUCK FAILED FOLLOWING APPROXIMATELY 2-3 GALLONS OF MATERIAL TO ESCAPE ONTO TO PAVEMENT OF THE TRANSFER FACILITY'S SCALE AREA. CLEAN HARBORS PERSONNEL AT THE SCENE IMMEDIATELY CONTAINED THE RELEASE AND ABSORBED ALL FREE LIQUIDS WITH SPEEDI DRY. ALL CLEAN UP DEBRIS WAS CONTAINERIZED AND SENT TO CLEAN HARBORS OF BRAINTREE, INC. FOR DISPOSAL. THE VEHICLE WAS THEN OFF-LOADED AND WAS PLACED OUT OF SERVICE UNTIL THE LEVEL GAGE WAS REPAIRED. PRIOR TO DEPARTURE FROM THE SHIPPER'S LOCATION, THE VEHICLE WAS INSPECTED AND NO EVIDENCE OF LEAKING WAS OBSERVED. ALL DRIVERS WILL CONTINUE TO CONDUCT THOROUGH PRE AND POST TRIP INSPECTIONS IN ORDER TO IDENTIFY ANY MECHANICAL DEFECTS WITH EACH PIECE OF EQUIPMENT OPERATED. IN ADDITION, IN ORDER TO PREVENT A RECURRENCE OF THIS INCIDENT, CLEAN HARBORS INSPECTED AND REPLACED THE LIQUID LEVEL GAGES ON SEVERAL OTHER PIECES OF EQUIPMENT THAT WERE PURCHASED AT THE SAME TIME AS THE VEHICLE THAT EXPERIENCED THE RELEASE

column42: COMPOUND, CLEANING, LIQUID (CONTAINING PHOSPHORIC ACID, ACETIC ACID, SODIUM HYDROXIDE OR POTASSIUM HYDROXIDE)
column168: A VAN TRAILER CONTAINING HAZARDOUS WASTE WAS ENROUTE FROM CLEAN HARBORS OF BALTIMORE INC. LOCATED AT  1910 RUSSELL STREET IN BALTIMORE MD TO CLEAN HARBORS IN BRISTOL CT. DURING THE COURSE OF THE TRIP, THE DRIVER DISCOVERED THAT A SMALL AMOUNT OF PRODUCT WAS ESCAPING FROM THE REAR DOOR OF THE VAN TRAILER HE WAS OPERATING. THE DRIVER IMMEDIATELY PLACED POLYETHYLENE SHEETING AND ABSORBENT MATERIAL UNDER THE AREA OF THE VEHICLE EXPERIENCING THE RELEASE AND CALLED HIS DISPATCHER FOR ASSISTANCE. THE DRIVER'S DISPATCHER DISPATCHED A CLEAN-UP CREW TO THE SCENE IN ORDER TO IDENTIFY THE CAUSE OF THE RELEASE AND TO INITIATE CORRECTIVE ACTIONS. UPON ARRIVAL AT THE SCENE, THE CLEANUP CREW INSPECTED THE LOAD AND DISCOVERED THAT APPROXIMATELY 10-20 GALLONS OF A PHOSPHORIC ACID CLEANING COMPOUND HAD ESCAPED FROM A 110 GALLON SALVAGE DRUM ONTO THE FLOOR OF THE VAN TRAILER. IT WAS ESTIMATED THAT 1-2 GALLONS OF MATERIAL ESCAPED FROM THE VAN TRAILER ONTO THE CONTAINMENT SYSTEM SET UP BY THE DRIVER. INSPECTION OF THE CONTAINER IN QUESTION REVEALED THAT THE CONTENTS OF THE DRUM PACKAGED WITHIN THE 110 GALLON SALVAGE DRUM HAD REACTED WITH THE ABSORBENT MATERIAL PLACED IN THE SALVAGE CAUSING A HOLE TO DEVELOP IN THE BOTTOM OF THE SALVAGE DRUM. THE CLEAN-UP CREW THEN ABSORBED ALL FREE LIQUIDS WITH SPEEDI-DRY, RECONTAINERIZED THE DAMAGED CONTAINER AND CONTAINERIZED ALL SPILL DEBRIS FOR SHIPMENT TO CLEAN HARBORS OF CONNECTICUT, INC FOR DISPOSAL. PRIOR TO DEPARTURE FROM THE SHIPPER'S LOCATION, THE LOAD WAS INSPECTED AND NO EVIDENCE OF LEAKING OR DAMAGE WAS OBSERVED. ALL DRIVERS AND LOADING PERSONNEL WILL CONTINUE TO INSPECT EACH CONTAINER AS IT IS LOADED AND TAKE APPROPRIATE ACTIONS IN THE EVENT A CONTAINER IS FOUND NOT BE PROPERLY CLOSED OR NOT STRUCTURALLY SOUND. IN ADDITION, THE SHIPPER HAS BEEN INSTRUCTED TO UTILIZE ABSORBENT MATERIALS THAT ARE COMPATIBLE WITH THE LADING TO PREVENT A RECURRENCE OF THIS INCIDENT.

THE HOLE WAS CAUSED BY ACID BETWEEN BFG 2002-B10-9, URS 5323 LINED RUBBER LINING AND OUTER STEEL SHELL. A 8"X12" STEEL PATCH WITH RUBBER BACKING WAS PLACED OVER THE HOLE AND HELD IN PLACE BY TWO STEEL BANDS WRAPPED AROUND THE OUTER SHELL OF THE CAR. THE CAR WAS STENCILED, "LEAKY TANK-DO NOT LOAD UNTIL REPAIRED," WITH SYMBOL* BY THE HOLE. WE THEN CONTACTED GENERAL AMERICAN TRANSPORTATION CORPORATION  FOR HOME SHOP DISPOSITION.

THE DRIVER SHUT THE VALVE TO STOP THE SPILL. SPILLED LIQUID WAS DIKED FOR CONTAINMENT, THEN THE DRIVER USED ABSORBENT TO CLEAN UP THE SPILL AND PACKAGED IT FOR PROPER DISPOSAL. column168: A VAPOR LEAK THOUGHT TO BE NEAR THE INLET VALVE ON A TANK CAR WAS DETECTED BY A BUFFALO & PITTSBURGH RAILROAD CAR INSPECTOR. HE IMMEDIATELY ADVISED THE YARD MASTER OF THE SITUATION. CHEMTREC WAS CALLED AND ASSISTED IN CONTACTING THE SHIPPER. THE SHIPPER, MOBIL OIL AND BPRR REPRESENTATIVES ARRANGED FOR A PRECAUTIONARY RESPONSE BY A LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT UNTIL AN ASSESSMENT OF THE SITUATION WAS COMPLETED. THE LEAK WAS DETERMINED TO BE COMING FROM THE SAFETY RELIEF VALVE CAUSED BY THE CAR BEING OVERLOADED. TEMPORARY MEASURES WERE TAKEN TO SECURE THE LEAK. THE CAR WAS ISOLATED AND HELD FOR A PARTIAL TRANSFER INTO ANOTHER CAR. MOBIL OIL'S EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR (OHM) RESPONDED AND COORDINATED THE TRANSFER WHICH WAS COMPLETED AT 1300 HOURS ON JUNE 17, 1995. BOTH CARS WENT ON TO MOBIL OIL IN MARYSVILLE, MICHIGAN, THE ORIGINAL DESTINATION. THERE WERE NO ENVIRONMENTAL CONCERNS.
TRAILER LATCH BROKE, DOOR ON TRAILER OPENED, AND CARTON FELL TO ROAD BREAKING TWO (2) ONE GALLON CONTAINERS. MATERIAL RECOOPED AND RETURNED TO SHIPPER.

IN THE PROCESS OF LOADING FREIGHT IN TRLR 19-1048 A PALLET OF AT&T TELEPHONES HIT THS H\M SHIPMENT AND CAUSED OF PUNCTURE ON ONE OF THE CONTAINERS CONTAINING THIS HAZARDOUS MATERIAL. AS A RESULT 2 GALLONS OF THIS PRODUCT LEAKED OUT OF THE 2 1/2 GALLON CONTAINER ONTO THE FLOOR OF THE TRAILER.

column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: OUR TRUCK  WAS TRAVELING ON A TWO LANE ROAD, WHEN THE DRIVER WAS FORCED INTO A FARM DRIVEWAY BY TWO ONCOMING CARS. HE FAILED TO MAKE THE TURN AND THE TRACTOR/TRAILER TURNED OVER ON ITS RIGHT SIDE. THE DRIVER MADE CONTACT WITH THE DUNKERTON, IA FIRE DEPT, AND THEY, ALONG WITH BLACKHAWK COUNTY SHERIFF'S DEPT, RESPONDED IMMEDIATELY. UPON ARRIVAL THEY FOUND THAT OUR LOADED TRAILER WAS INTACT EXCEPT FOR SOME PIPING AND VALVES THAT HAD BROKEN UPON IMPACT WITH THE GROUND. THEY THEN PROCEEDED TO OFF-LOAD THE PRODUCT ONTO ANOTHER TRAILER, TO AVOID ANY FURTHER SPILLAGE THAT MAY HAVE OCCURRED IN THE PROCESS OF PULLING THE RIG OUT OF THE DITCH. AT FIRST, THE SPILL SEEMED TO VERY MINIMAL, BUT WHEN THE GREATER LOSS WAS DETECTED AT THE CONSIGNEES DESTINATION, THE DNR WERE CALLED IN TO ACCESS THE SITUATION AND GIVE THEIR RECOMMENDATIONS FOR CLEAN UP.

WHAT ACTUALLY CAUSED FAILURE IS UNKNOWN.  THE FOLLOWING IS A SYNOPSIS OF THE RESPONSE ACTIVITIES CONDUCTED BY WEAVERTOWN ENVIRONMENTAL GROUP (WEG), A DIVISION OF WEAVERTOWN TRANSPORT LEASING (WTL), FOR SCHNEIDER NATIONAL CARRIER CORPORATION ON JUNE 22, 1995.  GREENE COUNTY, PENNSYLVANIA EMERGENCY MANAGEMENT AGENCY (EMA) CALLED FOR THE WEG HAZARDOUS MATERIALS RESPONSE UNIT, WHICH IS CONTRACTED WITH GREENE COUNTY FOR CERTIFIED HAZARDOUS MATERIALS RESPONSE AT APPROXIMATELY 2200 HOURS.  THE 911 DISPATCH CENTER INFORMED WEG PERSONNEL A SCHENIDER NATIONAL CARRIER TRAILER WAS IN A REST AREA IN THE NORTHBOUND OF INTERSTATE 79 BY THE KIRBY EXIT.  THE MATERIAL LEAKING WAS IDENTIFIED AS CHROMIC ACID/HYDROCHLORIC ACID SOLUTION IN 350-400 GALLON TOTES.  IT WAS REPORTED THAT ONE TOTE WAS LEAKING FROM A GASKET.  WEG CREWS ARRIVED ON SCENE AT 2330 HOURS.  THE MOUNT MORRIS COMMUNITY VOLUNTEER FIRE DEPARTMENT AND JEFFREY MARSHALL, DEPUTY DIRECTOR OF GREENE COUNTY EMA WERE ON SCENE.  AFTER AN ASSESSMENT AND INTERVIEW WITH THE DRIVER, WEG NOTIFIED THE FIRE DEPARTMENT THAT NO IMMINENT DANGER WAS PRESENT AND THE OPTION WAS UP TO THEM IF THEY WISHED TO STAY.  THE FIRE DEPARTMENT LEFT THE SCENE SLIGHTLY AFTER 2400 HOURS, EMA REMAINED ON SCENE.  PERSONNEL ENTERED THE TRAILER AND CLEANED ALL VISIBLE SIGNS OF CHROMIC ACID CONTAMINATION USING A SODIUM HYDROXIDE SOLUTION AND UNIVERSAL PADS.  THE LEAK WAS DETERMINED TO BE FROM THE OUTSIDE EDGE OF THE TOTE FOUND SECOND-IN ON THE DRIVER'S SIDE.  THE EDGE APPEARED TO HAVE BEEN BROKEN OR CUT.  THERE WERE NO INDICATIONS THAT THIS OCCURRED DURING TRANSIT.  THE LEAK AS WELL AS THE LIDS WERE SEALED WITH CAULKING AND GASKET FORM.  THE TOTES WERE MOVED TO DECONTAMINATE AS MUCH AS POSSIBLE.

column168: OUR DRIVER WAS IN THE PROCESS OF TRANSFERRING THE MATERIAL TO STORAGE AT HIS DESTINATION WHEN AN OCCASIONAL DRIP OF PRODUCT WAS DETECTED FROM THE FITTING CONNECTING THE HOSE TO THE CUSTOMER'S STORAGE TANK. A BUCKET WITH NEUTRALIZER WAS PLACED UNDER THE DRIP TO COMPLETE THE UNLOADING. WHEN THE PLANT RECEIVER DISCONNECTED THE HOSE FROM THEIR STORAGE TANK THERE WAS A SMALL AMOUNT OF MATERIAL THAT SPILLED ONTO THE GROUND. THE SPILL AREA WAS CLEANED UP BY THE RECEIVER.

OUR DRIVER HAD BEEN CLEARED FOR DELIVERY. HE HOOKED UP THE TRANSFER HOSES AND ENGAGED HIS PRODUCT PUMP. AT THIS POINT, THE HOSE PULLED LOOSE FROM THE HOSE CONNECTION AT THE DISCHARGE SIDE OF THE PUMP. OUR DRIVER SHUT DOWN AND FOUND THAT THE CONSIGNEE HAD FAILED TO OPEN THE VALVE ON THE STORAGE TANK. THIS CAUSED EXCESS PRESSURE AND THE HOSE SEPARATED FROM THE HOSE END. THE HOSE WAS CHANGED, THE VALVE OPENED AND DELIVERY WAS COMPLETED. THE SPILL AREA WAS CLEANED UP BY CONSIGNEE.

OUR DRIVER HAD BEEN CLEARED FOR DELIVERY. HE PROCEEDED TO TRANSFER THE CARGO TO STORAGE. AS OUR TRAILER EMPTIED ON THE CUSTOMER'S STORAGE TANK OVERFLOWED. THE CUSTOMER HAD IMPROPERLY GAUGED HIS STORAGE CAPACITY. THE SPILLED PRODUCT WAS TAKEN CARE OF BY THE CONSIGNEE.

OUR DRIVER LOADED AT THE SHIPPER'S FACILITY. THE ACTUAL LOADING WAS HANDLED BY SHIPPER PERSONNEL. AFTER LOADING HE WAS LEAVING THE SHIPPER'S FACILITY AND AS HE TURNED ONTO CLARK ST HE NOTED LIQUID RUNNING FROM THE DISCHARGE LINE. HE STOPPED AND SET OUT WARNING TRIANGLES AND NOTIFIED THE SHIPPER AND HIS TERMINAL OF THE PROBLEM. IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT THE LOADER HAD FAILED TO CLOSE THE VALVE AND OUR DRIVER FAILED TO MAKE SURE THE LOAD WAS PROPERLY SECURED. PERSONNEL WERE DISPATCHED TO CLEAN UP THE SPILL AREA.

column168: DRIVER CONNECTED TRACTOR TO TANKER AT 0245 HRS ON 063095 TO PREPARE FOR DELIVERY. WHILE PERFORMING PRE-TRIP CHECK. DRIVER FAILED TO NOTE THAT BALL VALVE ON AIR BLOW DOWN LINE WAS NOT FULLY CLOSED. DRIVER/VEHICLE LEFT FACILITY AT 0300 HRS SAME DAY. ANOTHER DRIVER, WHO WAS FOLLOWING, NOTICED LIQUID COMING OUT OF BLOW DOWN HOSE DRIVER # 2 ALERTS DRIVER #1 VIA CB RADIO. DRIVER #1 STOPS VEHICLE, CHECKS VALVES AND IMMEDIATELY RETURNS TO FACILITY (2-3 BLOCKS) DRIVER #1 ALERTS SUPERVISOR OF PROBLEM. SPILLAGE OCCURRED WHEN PRODUCT SPLASHES INTERNALLY AND MIGRATES TO AN OPENING. MANLEY-REGAN CERT TEAM WAS ACTIVATED @0318 HRS. LOCAL MIDDLETOWN EMA WAS ALERTED AT 0318 HRS, LOCAL HAZ MAT RESPONSE. MANLEY-REGAN CERT TEAM LEADER ARRIVED ON SITE AT 0345, RE-IDENTIFIED PRODUCT, INSTRUCTED DRIVER TO RE-WEIGH VEHICLE FOR LOSS CONFIRMATION, AND BEGAN CLEAN-UP ACTIVITIES. CERTEAM BEGINS CLEAN-UP AT 0345, APPLIES ABSORBENT AND COLLECTS. ABSORBENT/PRODUCT CLEANED OFF STREET, PLACED IN PROPER CONTAINER, LABELED, PLACED IN STAGING AREA FOR REMOVAL BY CONTRACT HAZ-WASTE COMPANY-NO MANIFEST TO DATE- PREVENTION: NEW LOCKOUT BILL VALVES PURCHASED TO INSTALL ON ALL TANKERS, NEW TRAINING PROCEDURE BEING DEVELOPED.

column42: PAINT RELATED MATERIAL INCLUDING PAINT THINNING, DRYING, REMOVING, OR REDUCING COMPOUND
column168: A VAN TRAILER CONTAINING HAZARDOUS WASTE WAS ENROUTE FROM CLEAN HARBORS OF NATICK, INC LOCATED AT 10 MERCER ROAD IN NATICK, MA TO ENSCO, INC. LOCATED AT AMERICAN OIL ROAD IN EL DORADO, AR. DURING THE COURSE OF THE TRIP, THE DRIVER MADE A ROUTINE STOP IN ORDER TO CONDUCT A LOAD AND TIRE CHECK AND DISCOVERED THAT APPROXIMATELY  1.5 GALLONS OF PAINT RELATED MATERIAL HAD ESCAPED FROM ONE OF THE CONTAINERS ONTO THE FLOOR OF THE VAN TRAILER WHERE IT WAS PREVENTED FROM ESCAPING TO THE ENVIRONMENT. THE DRIVER IMMEDIATELY CONTACTED HIS DISPATCHER WHO DISPATCHED A CLEAN-UP CREW TO THE SCENE IN ORDER TO IDENTIFY THE CAUSE OF THE RELEASE AND TO INITIATE CORRECTIVE ACTIONS. UPON ARRIVAL AT THE SCENE, THE CLEAN-UP CREW INSPECTED THE LOAD AND DISCOVERED THAT THE POLYETHYLENE LINER WAS PUNCTURED BY AN INNER PACKAGING THAT HAD BROKEN ALLOWING THE MATERIAL TO ESCAPE THROUGH THE FIBERBOARD BOX ONTO THE FLOOR OF THE VAN TRAILER. THE CREW THEN ABSORBED ALL FREE LIQUIDS WITH SPEEDI DRY AND REPACKAGED THE DAMAGED CONTAINER ALONG WITH ALL CLEAN-UP DEBRIS FOR CONTINUING TRANSPORT TO THE WASTE MANAGEMENT FACILITY INDICATED ON THE SHIPPING DOCUMENT. PRIOR TO DEPARTURE FROM THE SHIPPER'S LOCATION, THE LOAD WAS INSPECTED AND NO EVIDENCE OF LEAKING OR DAMAGE WAS OBSERVED. ALL DRIVERS AND LOADING PERSONNEL WILL CONTINUE TO INSPECT EACH CONTAINER AS IT IS LOADED AND TAKE APPROPRIATE ACTIONS IN THE EVENT A CONTAINER IS FOUND NOT TO BE PROPERLY CLOSED OR NOT STRUCTURALLY SOUND. THE SHIPPER HAS BEEN RE-INSTRUCTED TO INSURE THAT ALL INNER PACKAGINGS ARE SECURE AND SUFFICIENTLY CUSHIONED WITH ABSORBENT MATERIAL TO PREVENT THE INNER LINER FROM BEING PUNCTURED.

column168: THE TRAILER WAS IN THE PROCESS OF BEING LOADED WHEN A LEAK WAS NOTICED COMING FROM THE SKIN OF THE TRAILER. ONCE LOAD WAS CONTAINED, IT WAS MOVE TO THE RINECO FACILITY IN BENTON WHERE IT WAS OFFLOADED. THE TRAILER FLOOR WAS CLEANED BY TSD PERSONNEL. NO FURTHER PROBLEMS WERE ENCOUNTERED.

column168: OUR UNIT WAS D.O.T. INSPECTED AT APPROX 0700 AT KNOXVILLE, TN. WITH NO VIBRATIONS NOTED. WHEN DRIVER ARRIVED AT WEIGH STATION ON I-70 NORTH OF COLUMBUS, OHIO AT APPROX 1400 HRS., CORROSIVE PLACARD WAS NOT ON REAR OF TRAILER. P.U.C.O. INSTRUCTED DRIVER TO PARK IN REAR OF SCALES. THE LEAK WAS DISCOVERED AFTER TRUCK WAS PARKED. NO LEAK WAS DETECTED AS TRUCK WAS CROSSING SCALES. ACCORDING TO P.U.C.O. OFFICER. THE DRUM WAS OVERHANGING THE EDGE OF PALLET. VIBRATION POSSIBLY CAUSED THE DRUM TO CRACK. SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED IMMEDIATELY UPON OUR KNOWLEDGE OF INCIDENT. WE ALSO NOTIFIED A CLEAN-UP CREW BASED IN LANCASTER, OHIO. THEY WERE ON THE SCENE WITHIN 11/2 HOURS.

A VAN TRAILER CONTAINING HAZARDOUS WASTE WAS ENROUTE FROM ARCO CHEMICAL COMPANY LOCATED AT 400 FRANKFORT ROAD IN MONACA, PA TO CLEAN HARBORS OF BALTIMORE, INC. LOCATED AT 1910 RUSSELL STREET IN BALTIMORE, MD. DURING THE COURSE OF THE TRIP, THE DRIVER WAS FORCED TO MAKE A SUDDEN STOP IN ORDER TO AVOID A PASSENGER VEHICLE THAT HAD SUDDENLY BRAKED SHARPLY IN FRONT OF HIM. THE RAPID DECELARATION OF THE VEHICLE CAUSED THE LOAD TO SHIFT DAMAGING ONE CONTAINER. APPROXIMATELY 5 GALLONS OF MATERIAL ESCAPED FROM THE DAMAGED DRUM ONTO THE FLOOR OF THE VAN TRAILER WHERE IT WAS PREVENTED FROM ESCAPING TO THE ENVIRONMENT. THE DRIVER IMMEDIATELY CONTACTED HIS DISPATCHER WHO DISPATCHED A CLEAN-UP CREW TO THE SCENE IN ORDER TO INITIATE CORRECTIVE ACTIONS. UPON ARRIVAL AT THE SCENE THE CLEAN-UP CREW ABSORBED ALL FREE LIQUIDS WITH SPEEDI DRY, PLACED THE DAMAGED CONTAINER INTO A SUITABLE SALVAGE DRUM AND CONTAINERIZED A SPILL DEBRIS. ALL DEBRIS GENERATED AS A RESULT OF THIS INCIDENT WAS SENT TO THE WASTE MANAGEMENT FACILITY INDICATED ON THE SHIPPING DOCUMENT. PRIOR TO DEPARTURE FROM THE SHIPPER'S LOCATION, THE LOAD WAS INSPECTED AND ALL BLOCKING AND BRACING DEVICES (I.E. THE LOAD WAS INSPECTED AND ALL BLOCKING AND BRACING DEVICES (I.E LOAD LOCKS) WERE IN PLACE. IT IS BELIEVED THAT THE SUDDEN DECELARATION OF THE VEHICLE CAUSED THE CONTAINERS TO DISPLACE THE LOADLOCKS ALLOWING THE DRUMS TO CRUSH AGAINST EACH OTHER. ALL DRIVERS AND LOADING PERSONNEL WILL CONTINUE TO INSPECT EACH SHIPMENT AND INSURE THAT APPROPRIATE BLOCKING AND BRACING DEVICES ARE IN PLACE AND OPERATIONAL.

column168: JUNE 22, 1995, APPROXIMATELY 1910 HOURS, GAULEY BRIDGE FIRE DEPARTMENT NOTICED ODOR IN VICINITY OF RAIL AND NOTIFIED DUPONT. DUPONT RESPONDED REPLACING DOME GASKET. CAR RELEASED TO TRANSPORTATION FORWARDING RAIL CAR TO OWNER'S SHOP FOR CLEANING AND RELEASE FROM SERVICE.

COFC, UPLU911634 ON TWX 922273 WAS DISCOVERED LEAKING IN BACK YARD, RIVERDALE, IL. CAR WAS ISOLATED IN YARD OVER RETENTION PIT. COFL WAS LEAKING CLEAR LIQUID AT A RATE OF 1 GALLON OVER 5 MINUTES. OUTSIDE CONCERN, HERITAGE REMEDITATION WAS DISPATCHED TO ASSESS THE LEAK. ACTUAL CONDITIONS WERE THE CONTAINER WHICH WAS NOT COMPLETELY SEALED DUE TO AN OBSTRUCTION BETWEEN GASKET AND PLATE. REMOVAL OF OBSTRUCTION PERMITTED A SEAL. CONTAINER WAS NOT LEAKING AFTER HASP TIGHTENED.

WHEN DRUM WAS PULLED OF MEM INBOUND TRL IT WAS CHECKED AND PUT OUT FOR DELIVERY. NOTHING WAS LEAKING AT TIME OF DELIVERY. WHEN OUR DRIVER HAD THIS OUT FOR DELIVERY THERE WAS A SMALL HOLE IN THE DRUM BUT NOTHING WAS LEAKING, DUE TO THE FACT THE ADHESIVE HAD SEALED THE HOLE. THE HOLE WAS DISCOVERED BY THE CONSIGNEE AND WAS REFUSED. DURING TRANSIT BACK TO OUR TERMINAL, THE HOLE HAD COME UNSEALED AND LEAKED OUT INTO THE TRAILER APPROX AMOUNT OF 32 OZC, THEN THE HOLE RESEALED IT SELF AND STOPPED LEAKING. PUT THE REST OF THE ADHESIVE IN A RECOVERY DRUM AND SENT BACK TO SHIPPER FOR TESTING.

BOXES OF PYRIDINE BEING UNLOADED FROM TRAILER IN WEST MIDDLESEX, PA WHEN DAMAGED NOTICED. BOXES WERE NOTICED TO BE LEAKING. PACKAGING CONTAINED GLASS BOTTLES. BOTTLES BROKEN IN PACKING. WITH BETTER PACKAGING THIS INCIDENT WOULD HAVE BEEN PREVENTED.

SWITCH CREW DETECTED AMMONIA SMELL FROM TANK CAR DELIVERED BY SP TO ATSF YARD IN REGULAR INTERCHANGE CUT. YARD OPERATIONS WERE SUSPENDED IN THE IMMEDIATE AREA. SEVEN ATSF EMPLOYEES WERE IMPACTED; HOWEVER, THERE WAS NO PUBLIC EVACUATION. ATSF RESPONDERS ASSESSED THE CAR AND DETERMINED THE SOURCE OF THE RELEASE TO BE FROM THE PROTECTIVE HOUSING AREA. THE CAR WAS RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER'S FACILITY AT 1630 PT USING A SUPERVISORY CREW. IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE CAR HAD BEEN FOUND LEAKING WHILE IN THE SP YARD. THE SHIPPER HAD INSPECTED THE CAR AND DETERMINED THAT THE B END LIQUID VALVE WAS DEFECTIVE. THE CAR WAS TO HAVE BEEN RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER BY THE SP FOR OFF LOADING. INSTEAD, THE CAR WAS ADDED TO THE ROUTINE INTERCHANGE CUT DELIVERED TO THE ATSF, AND WITHOUT ANY SPECIAL INSTRUCTIONS CONCERNING THE LEAKING CONDITION. AS A RESULT OF THIS INCIDENT AND A PREVIOUS INCIDENT IN MAY, THE SHIPPER, IN CONJUNCTION WITH DISCUSSIONS INVOLVING THE CALIFORNIA PUBLIC UTILITIES COMMISSION, AGREED TO USING 5% OUTAGE FOR THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPPING SEASON.

TANK CAR FOUND LEAKING BY OUTBOUND TRAIN CREW AT AMARILLO YARD. ATSF RESPONDERS DETERMINED SOURCE OF LEAK TO BE FITTINGS ON MANWAY LID. A 2 INCH PIPE PLUG WAS LEAKING DUE TO THREADS PERMITTING PRODUCT TO PASS. CONTAINMENT POOL WAS PLACED UNDER THE CAR. PLUG WAS REMOVED, PVC PIPE TAPE USED, AND THE PLUG WAS REAPPLIED. CAPTURED LIQUID AND SMALL AREA ON GROUND WERE NEUTRALIZED WITH SODA. CAR SIDES WERE ALSO RINSED WITH SODA SOLUTION.

CUSTOMER WANTED 350 GALLONS INTO TWO 275 GALLON TANKS WHICH LOOKED IN VERY GOOD CONDITION. I PUT 174.1 GALLONS OF FUEL INTO THE FIRST TANK WITH NO PROBLEM,THEN WENT TO OTHER TANK TO FINISH ORDER WHEN I SPOTTED LEAK. WHILE PUTTING THE FUEL IN, THE TANK DID NOT LEAK AT ALL. 1. I TOOK OIL PADS FROM TRUCK AND PUT THEM INTO WHERE THE FUEL WAS COMING OUT SO FLOW OF SPILL WOULD STOP. 2. I WENT BACK TO THE TRUCK TO CALL THE OFFICE TO LET THEM KNOW OF THE SPILL, AND LET THEM KNOW I NEEDED HELP. 3. I WENT BACK TO THE TANKS TO KEEP AN EYE ON THEM AND MAKE SURE THAT NO MORE FUEL WOULD COME OUT. 4. NOTIFIED CUSTOMER RIGHT AWAY. CUSTOMER SENT A FOREMAN TO THE SPILL AND SAID NOT TO WORRY ABOUT THE TANK. I LET HIM KNOW THAT THE TANK WHICH ONLY LOST 4 GALLONS WAS STILL AT RISK OF SPILLING THE REST ON THE GROUND AND I DID NOT WANT TO LEAVE UNTIL HELP CAME TO PUMP THE FUEL INTO THE OTHER TANK. 5. WHEN HELP CAME, I BEGAN TO PUMP THE FUEL INTO OTHER TANK. WHEN PUMP OUT WAS DONE, THE TANK 2, WHICH HAD NO FUEL BEFORE THEN, HAD 29 1/2. 6. THE CLEAN UP WAS TO DIG UP THE DIRT WHICH HAD THE FUEL AND PUT NEW DIRT DOWN.

ON TUESDAY, 6/14/94 ABOUT 11:45 PM, I JUST GOT DONE LOADING TRAILER #74. I LIFTED THE SPOUT OUT OF THE TRAILER AND WIPED OFF THE BLACK OIL AND PUSHED IT OUT OF THE WAY. WHEN I BENT OVER TO CLOSE HATCH ON TRAILER & WIPE SOME OIL OFF TRAILER, THE LOADING ARM CAME DOWN AND HIT ME ONT HE HEAD, KNOCKING MY HELMET OFF AND GOT OIL ALL OVER ME AND THE TRAILER. THE ARM WAS HOT AND I COULDN'T GET IT BACK INTO THE TRAILER. I TRIED TO SHUT IT OFF, BUT IT WOULDN'T SHUT OFF. I PUSHED THE ARM BACK AND WENT FOR EMERGENCY SHUT OFF. DIDN'T WORK. THIS LETTER IS TO INFORM YOU OF A PACKAGING FAILURE OF A PORTABLE TANK SHIPPED UNDER EXEMPTION DOT-3 9052.  THE FAILURE OCCURRED ON JUNE 6, 1995. THE SHIPPING LOCATION WAS PARKER AMCHEM, CALHOUND, JUNE 6, 1995.  THE SHIPPING LOCATION WAS PARKER AMCHEM, CALHOUND, GEORGIA.  THE TRANSPORTER WAS RANGER TRANSPORTATION COMPANY.  THE PRODUCT WAS BEING SHIPPED TO AMERICAN NATIONAL CAN IN LONGVIEW, TEXAS.  THERE WERE TEN PORTABLE TANKS ON THE LOAD ALL CONTAINING A PRODUCT CONSISTING OF A SOLUTION OF ABOUT 20 PERCENT HYDROFLUORIC ACID.  THE RANGER DRIVER NOTICED PRODUCT LEAKING FROM THE TRAILER AT A TRUCK STOP IN MARSHALL, TEXAS.  INITIAL INVESTIGATION SHOWED THAT ONE OF THE TANKS HAD CRACKED ACROSS THE TOP, ABOVE THE LIQUID LINE, NEXT TO THE CLOSURE, ALLOWING PRODCUT TO SLOSH OUT OF THE TANK.  THE SPILLED MATERIAL WAS CONTAINED, AND CLEANED UP BY EMC OF FORT WORTH, TEXAS.  THE REMAINING PRODUCT WAS TRANSFERRED TO RECOVERY DRUMS.  THE ORIGINAL NET WEIGHT IN THE TANK WAS 2,820 POUNDS.  ABOUT 2,740 POUNDS OF PRODUCT WAS RECOVERED.  THE NET LOSS WAS ABOUT 80 POUNDS (OR 16 POUNDS OF HYDROFLUORIC ACID WHICH IS LESS THAN THE 100 POUND REPORTABLE QUANTITY FOR HYDROFLUORIC ACID).  THE FAILED TANK, PARKER AMCHEM NUMBER 0836 AND HOOVER SERIAL NUMBER 19379, WAS LAST TESTED PER THE EXEMPTION REQUIREMENTS, IN NOVEMBER, 1994.

ON JUNE 07, 1995 AT APPROXIMATELY 0200 HOURS DOCKMAN G HOYNOSKI ADVISED FREIGHT OPERATION MANAGER TODD KENNEY THERE WAS A STRONG ODOR COMING FROM TRAILER 17-1571. MR. HOYNOSKI HAD JUST BEEN ASSIGNED THIS TRAILER TO UNLOAD AND HAD NOTICED THE ODOR WHEN HE OPENED THE DOOR. THE F.O.M. DISCOVERED THE TRAILER HAD POISON ON IT AND HAD IT TAKEN TO AN ISOLATED AREA IN THE YARD UNTIL IT COULD BE DETERMINED WHAT WAS CAUSING THE ODOR. OFFICE MANAGER SAM MARTINI APPROAHED THE TRAILER AT ABOUT 1600 HOURS, THERE WAS VERY LITTLE ODOR LEFT. SAM MARTINI DISCOVERED 1 CARTON ON PRO 724-098314 WITH WHAT APPEARED TO BE A WATER OR LIQUID STAIN MARK ON THE SIDE. THE CARTON CONTAINED FOUR 1 GALLON METAL CONTAINERS OF POISONOUS LIQUID N.O.S., 6.1 KEEP AWAY FROM FOOD STUFFS. ONE OF THE CONTAINERS WAS BENT ON THE BOTTOM AND EMPTY. THE AREA DIRECTLY UNDER THE BOX IN QUESTION HAD TWO PIECES OF CARDBOARD, BOTH PIECES WERE DRY WITH NO MARKS OF MOISTURE ON EITHER ONE. IT APPEARS AS THOUGH THE CARTON HAD EITHER LEAKED BEFORE BEING LOADED ON THIS TRAILER AT PROVIDENCE OR BEFORE IT WAS PICKED UP AT THE SHIPPERS DOCK. I INFORMED THE TERMINAL MANAGER OF FINDINGS. THE CARTON WAS RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER IN AN OVERPAK DRUM ALONG WITH THE CARDBOARD FOUND UNDER IT.

column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: OUR COMPANY DRIVER TRAVELING EAST BOUND ON MIDWAY 78 FAILED TO STOP AT THE INTERSECTION OF HIGHWAY 43 IN MARION COUNTY, AL, LOST CONTROL CAUSING THE TRACTOR AND TRAILER TO OVERTURN ONTO ITS LEFT SIDE. AS A RESULT OF THE OVERTURN, THE CARGO CONSISTING OF 72 DRUMS OF HYDROFLURIC ACID, UN1790, AND FOUR DRUMS OF SODIUM DE-FLOURIDE, UN2439, ESCAPED FROM THE OVERTURNED TRAILER. DUE TO THE NATURE OF THE CHEMICALS AND AT THE DIRECTION OF RICKY MCWHARTER OF THE ALABAMA EPA, FIRE CHIEF BILL LOWDEN AND POLICE CHIEF, MAX BRASHER OF THE CITY OF HAMILTON, AN AREA OF A QUARTER MILE RADIUS WAS EVACUATED. THE AREA CONTAINED FOUR TO SIX FAMILIES ALONG WITH A TRUCK STOP AND RESTAURANT COMBINATION. LIQUID CHEMICALS ALSO ESCAPED INTO A NEARBY CREEK THAT RAN INTO A STREAM. THE REMEDIAL SERVICES LAID BOOMS PRIOR TO THE CONTAMINATED WATER REACHING THE RIVER, HOWEVER, WE UNDERSTAND MR. HAFFNER WITH ALABAMA FISH AND GAME DEPARTMENT HAS REPORTED AN UNDETERMINED LOSS OF SMALL FISH. THE TRACTOR DID SUFFER INJURIES AS A RESULT OF THE OVERTURN, HOWEVER, WAS NOT EXPOSED TO THE CHEMICALS. A PASSERBY STOPPED AND ATTEMTPED TO ASSIST THE DRIVER. IT IS REPORTED HE WAS EXPOSED, TREATED AND HAS BEEN RELEASED. ALL CONTAMINATED SOIL WAS PLACED IN ROLL-OFF BOXES FOR TRANSPORT TO AN APPROVED LAND FILL. ANY DRUMS THAT STILL CONTAINED EITHER OF THE CHEMICALS WERE PLACED IN OVERPACKS AND RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER. CONTAMINATED CLOTHING AND OTHER MATERIALS WERE DISPOSED OF IN A SIMILAR MANNER AT THE LAND FILL. THE CHEMICALS REQUIRED THE SERVICE PEOPLE TO WEAR LEVEL A SUITING ALONG WITH BREATHING APPARTUS. DUE TO THE EXTREME HEAT IT TOOK APPROXIMATELY SIXTY HOURS BEFORE THE AREA WAS SECURED AND THE HIGHWAY REOPENED FOR TRAFFIC. SEE REPORT 95061128A

column168: OUR DRIVER WAS MAKING A BULK DELIVERY OF KEROSENE TO THE ABOVE GROUND STORAGE TANKS AT AN ELECTRIC PLANT. WITH ONLY A FEW GALLONS LEFT ON OUR TRAILER, OUR DRIVER OBSERVED A BUBBLE DEVELOPING IN THE DELIVERY HOSE. INSTEAD OF STOPPING THE DELIVERY AND CHANGING HOSES, THE DRIVER CONTINUED TO PUMP THE LOAD OFF. THE BUBBLE BURST CAUSING AROUND 50 GALLONS OF KEROSENE TO SPRAY ONTO THE CEMENT CONTAINMENT PAD UNDER OUR TRUCK. THE KEROSENE WAS CLEANED UP WITH CLAY ABSORBANTS AND PADS. THE NEW YORK STATE DEPT OF ENVIRONMENTAL CONSERVATION WAS NOTIFIED AND THERE REFERENCE NUMBER FOR THIS INCIDENT IS 95-03003. OUR DRIVER WAS DISCIPLINED FOR NOT CHANGING HOSES WHEN THE PROBLEM WAS FIRST NOTICED.

column168: ON JUNE 6, 1995, AT 0337, A SPILL WITH AN ODOR WAS REPORTED BY HAZARDOUS MATERIAL SORT LEAD MARY LATHREM.  HAZARDOUS MATERIAL COORDINATOR ADDIE CAMPTON AND HAZRDOUS MATERIAL TECHNICAN RANDY WILLIAMS RESPONDED.  UPON ARRIVAL, WE NOTICED ONE CORNER OF THE FIRBERBOARD BOX WAS WET.  UPON FURTHER INSPECTION OF THE INNNER CONTENTS, WE FOUND ONE METAL RECEPTACLES IN A CLEAR PLASTIC BAG AND PACKED IN A FIBERBOARD BOX.  AFTER OPENING THE PLASTIC BAG, TECHNICAIN WILLIAMS DISCOVERED THAT THE SCREW TYPE CLOSURE WAS LOOSE.  AFTER REPACKING THE FIBERBOARD BOX AND PLACING IT IN A SALVAGE DRUM, WE DOCUMENTED THE REASON FOR THE LEAKAGE.  THIS WAS CLEARLY A HAZARDOUS MATERIAL AND FIBERBOARD BOX WAS CLEARLY MARKED AND LABELED AS A HAZARDOUS MATERIAL AND PROPER CERTIFICATION DID ACCOMPANY THIS SHIPMENT. THE ONLY THEORY WE HAVE FOR THIS SHIPMENT LEAKING AND HAVING AN ODOR WAS NOT HAVING POSITIVE MEAN TO SECURE THE CLOSURE.  CLEAR OF SCENE 0348.

INITIAL INSPECTION OF THE CONTAINER WAS CONDUCTED BY A FREIGHT CLAIMS INSPECTOR FOR THE RAILROAD, WHO STATED THE CONTENTS OF 55 GALLON DRUMS WERE LEAKING. THE EXTENT OF BLOCKING AND BRACING CONSISTED OF USED PALLETS STACKED BETWEEN THE REAR CONTAINER DOORS AND THE DRUMS STACKED ON THE SECOND LEVEL, WHICH IS INADEQUATE PER BOE6C FOR FLAMMABLE LIQUIDS. THE ORIGINAL SHIPPER OF THE PRODUCT MADE ARRANGEMENTS WITH THE RAILROAD CONTRACTOR TO TRANSLOAD THE CONTENTS AND DETERMINE THE EXTENT OF THE DAMAGE. A MARINE SURVEYOR REPRESENTING THE UNDERWRITERS FOR THE SHIPPER WAS ON SITE FOR THE TRANSLOAD OPERATION. TWO DAMAGED 55 GALLON DRUMS WERE LOCATED ON THE TOP LEVEL OF THE DOUBLE STACKED LOAD. ONE HAD BEEN CREASED IN THE SIDE JUST BELOW THE TOP CHIME, RESULTING IN A FIVE INCH LONG OPENING. THE SECOND LEVEL OF DRUMS WERE ON PALLETS, WITH NO SECUREMENT TO THE INDIVIDUAL PALLET. THE DRUM ADJACENT TO THE FIRST DAMAGED DRUM WAS OFF SET APPROXIMATELY ONE HALF INCH, WHICH ALLOWED THE TOP CHIME TO CONTINOUSLY RUB AGAINST THE DAMAGED DRUM DURING TRANSIT. THE SECOND DAMAGED DRUM WAS ALSO LOCATED ON THE TOP STACK. IT HAD SUSTAINED DAMAGE TO THE LOWER ROLLING HOOP FROM AN ADJACENT DRUM RUBBING AGAINST IT DURING TRANSIT. BOTH DRUMS WERE PLACED INTO OVERPACKS TO SECURE. AN ADDITIONAL DOZEN DRUM WERE LOCATED THAT WERE IN SUCH POOR CONDITION, THAT IT WAS DECIDED TO OVERPACK THESE DRUMS ALSO. A MAJORITY OF THE DRUMS IN THIS SHIPMENT WERE RECONDITIONED, HOWEVER, THE DRUMS WERE IN SUCH POOR CONDITION, THE INFORMATION REQUIRED FOR RECONDITIONED DRUMS WAS NOT LEGIBLE, THEREFORE, NOT RECORDED. THE CONTENTS WERE TRANSLOADED INTO A SECOND CONTAINER, MOLU288218, WHERE THEY WERE PROPERLY BLOCKED AND BRACED FOR MOVEMENT ONTO THE CONSIGNEE. THE ORIGINAL SHIPPING CONTAINER WAS CLEANED TO REMOVE THE BULK OF THE PAINT MATERIAL, HOWEVER, IT WILL HAVE TO SIT FOR SEVERAL DAYS TO TOTALLY DRY THE MATERIAL ON THE FLOORING, AT WHICH TIME THE OWNER, MITSUI WILL MAKE A DETERMINATION AS TO WHETHER THE FLOORING CAN BE FURTHER CLEANED OR MUST BE REPLACED.

0810 WEDNESDAY, JUNE 7, 1995, MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY STU WHITED WAS NOTIFIED BY SR. SPECIAL AGENT J. TRIOLA THAT CAR UTLX 13183 HAD BEEN REPORTED BY DOLTON CARMAN LEE JUSTICE. TRIOLA CONFIRMED CAR TO BE LEAKING FROM THE AREA OF THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE. WHITED IMMEDIATELY DEPARTED ST LOUIS FOR DOLTON AND AT THAT TIME NOTIFIED MANAGER MECHANICAL MAINTENCE R. WULF TO CHECK THE AREA OF THE LEAK AND TO PUT LIME ON THE GROUND BELOW THE LEAK. MR. WULF ADVISED THAT THE LEAK APPEARED TO BE AT THE FLANGE ON THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE WHERE VALVE BOLTS TO THE CAR. WHITED CONTACTED REGIONAL MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY T. M. ROBINSON AND WHO REPORTED LEAKING CAR TO CHEMTREC, SHIPPER FMC CORP., AND CONSIGNEE RHONE POULENCE AT CHICAGO HEIGHTS. MR. ALLAN WOOD, FMC, BEDFRORD PAR, CHICAGO, IL, RESPONDED TO THE LEAKING CAR AT WHICH TIME MR. WOOD FOUND TWO OF THE BOLTS ONE TURN LOOSE ON THE VALVE THAT SECURES THE VALVE TO THE TANK. LEAK SECURED AT 1255 HOURS. WHITED ARRIVED ON SITE AT 1300 HOURS AND MADE CHECK OF CAR IN COMPANY WITH MR WOOD AND WHO ADVISED THAT THIS WAS THE FIRST TRIP FOR CAR WHICH HAD JUST COME OUT OF THE SHOP. FURTHER CAR HAD BEEN IN THE DOLTON YARD CENTER YARD FOR TEN DAYS AND HAD NOT BEEN ORDERED INTO THE PLANT, WHEN LEAK WAS DISCOVERED. MR. WOOD ESTIMATED APPROXIMATELY THREE TO FOUR GALLONS OF PRODUCT WAS LOST AS A RESULT OF THE TWO LOOSE BOLTS ON THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE. FURTHER THAT WHEN CAR WAS OFF LOADED IT WOULD BE RETURNED TO THE SHOP. PHOSPHORIC ACID THAT WAS LEAKED FROM CAR UTLX 13183 WAS NEUTRALIZED WITH LIME AND LEFT ON SITE.

column42: PAINT INCLUDING PAINT, LACQUER, ENAMEL, STAIN, SHELLAC SOLUTIONS, VARNISH, POLISH, LIQUID FILLER AND LIQUID LACQUER BASE
column62: Dropped; Improper Preparation for Transportation; Inadequate Blocking and Bracing
column168: DEAN C. COOPER, MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS NOTIFIED BY ITS RAMP PERSONNEL THAT A CONTAINER WAS NOTED LEAKING WHAT APPEARED TO BE PAINT, WHILE IN THE EAST YARD INTERMODAL FACILITY. MANAGER COOPER DROVE TO THE FACILITY, INSPECTED THE CONTAINER, AND DEVELOPED THE SOURCE OF THE LEAK TO BE FROM THE LADING OF PAINT, WHICH WAS CONTAINED IN VARIOUS SIZED DRUMS AND PAILS. THE ENTIRE LADING WAS JUMBLED WITHIN THE CONTAINER. ALL OF THE VARIOUS SIZED DRUMS HAD BEEN PLACED ONTO PALLETS WITHOUT SECURING THE DRUMS TO THE PALLETS. THE ONLY SECUREMENT WAS A SINGLE PLASTIC BAND AROUND THE MIDSECTION OF THE DRUMS SITUATED ON EACH PALLET. IN EVERY CASE THE PLASTIC BAND HAD BEEN STRETCHED FROM THE DRUMS "DANCING" DURING TRANSIT AND WERE LAYING AT THE BASE OF THE DRUMS ON THE PALLET, THUS PROVIDING NO SECUREMENT. THE LOAD HAD BEEN SECURED AT THE REAR OF THE CONTAINER WITH TWO EACH, 2X4'S PLACED ACROSS THE WIDTH OF THE CONTAINER. THERE WAS A SECOND LAYER OF FOUR PALLETS CONTAINING 30 GALLON DRUMS ON TOP OF THE FLOOR LEVEL DRUMS, IN THE FOREWARD NOSE OF THE CONTAINER. OF THE TWO 2X4'S THAT HAD BEEN PLACED ACROSS THE WIDTH OF THE CONTAINER TO SECURE THE SECOND LEVEL DRUMS ONE HAD BROKEN NEAR THE CENTER AT A KNOT HOLE AND WAS LAYING IN TWO PIECES. THE OTHER HAD FALLEN AND WAS LAYING ON TOP OF THE FLOOR LEVEL DRUMS. ONCE THE PLASTIC BAND LOOSENED, THE DRUMS TOPPLED ONTO THE FLOOR LEVEL DRUMS. THE FIRST DAMAGED DRUM RELEASED ALL OF IT'S CONTENTS FROM TWO TEARS IN THE ROLLING HOOPS, SUSTAINED FROM IMPACTS WITH THE TOP CHIMES OF THE FLOOR LEVEL DRUMS. THE SECOND DRUM SUSTAINED DAMAGE FROM WHAT IS BELIEVED TO BE AN IMPACT WITH A RING CLOSURE BOLT FROM ONE OF THE FLOOR LEVEL DRUMS. THE IMPACT CAUSED A SMALL CRACK ON THE INSIDE BOTTOM CHIME, AND RESULTED IN LESS THAN A TWO GALLON RELEASE. THE ENTIRE LADING WAS REMOVED FROM THE CONTAINER IN ORDER TO INSPECT EACH DRUM. WHILE 95% OF THE LADING SHOWED SIGNS OF SEVERE METAL FATIGUE FROM RUBBING AGAINST OTHER ADJACENT DRUMS, ONLY THE TWO 30 GALLON DRUMS WERE FOUND TO HAVE RELEASED THEIR CONTENTS. THE DRUMS WERE RECOOPED ON PALLETS, STRETCH WRAPPED TO PREVENT MOVEMENT, AND RELOADED INTO TRAILER MPZ253410 FOR DELIVERY TO THE CONSIGNEE. AS THERE WAS NO BLOCKING BETWEEN THE PALLETS ON THE FLOOR TO PREVENT MOVEMENT, AND ONLY A SINGLE PLASTIC BAND AROUND THE DRUMS, AND NO ATTACHMENT OF THE DRUMS TO THE PALLETS, THE ENTIRE FLOOR LOAD MOVED WITHIN THE CONTAINER DURING TRANSIT. THIS MOVEMENT AFFECTED THE BRACING OF THE SECOND LEVEL LADING, WHICH WAS ALSO MISSING PLYWOOD SHEETS TO SEPARATE THE TWO LEVELS, WHICH ADDED TO THE FORCES ALLOWING THE DRUMS TO BREAK LOOSE AND TOPPLE. DUE TO THE AMOUNT AND TYPE OF PRODUCT RELEASED, NOTIFICATIONS WERE ONLY MADE TO CHEMTREC FOR REPORTING PURPOSES, AND TO THE SHIPPER FOR CORRECTIVE ACTION.

UNIT 246 SUFFERED ENGINE PROBLEMS (THE TURBO FAILED). BECAUSE THE ENGINE WAS STILL UNDER WARRANTY FROM CUMMINS, THE SALT LAKE CUMMINS DISTRIBUTED WAS CALLED FOR ASSISTANCE. CUMMINS DECIDED TO HAVE THE UNIT TOWED TO SALT LAKE FOR REPAIRS AND, SO, CALLED BULLOCKS TOWING AND ASK THEM TO TOW THE UNIT. IN ORDER FOR BULLOCKS TO TOW THE TRACTOR IT HAD TO BE UNHOOKED FROM THE SEMI. KIM HAMLIN CALLED EDDIE FURRH (BASIN WESTERN DISPATCHER) AND REQUESTED ANOTHER UNIT TO HOOK ONTO HIS SEMI AFTER UNHOOKING IT FROM UNIT 246. EDDIE DISPATCHED RANDY GILBERT ON UNIT 243 TO HOOK ONTO KIM'S TRAILERS. WHEN RANDY (UNIT 243) ARRIVED AT THE SITE OF THE BREAK-DOWN, HE AND KIM BORROWED BLOCKS FROM BULLOCK'S TOW TRUCK, PLACED THEM UNDER THE LANDING GEAR ON KIM'S TRAILER AND DOLLIED THE TRAILER DOWN. THE LANDING GEAR DOLLIES WERE BOTH ON THE PAVEMENT AT THE SHOULDER OF THE ROAD, HOWEVER, THE RIGHT TRAILER TIRES WERE OFF OF THE PAVEMENT RESULTING IN THE BACK OF THE TRAILER TIRES WERE OFF OF THE PAVEMENT RESULTING IN THE BACK OF THE TRAILER BEING SLIGHTLY UNLEVEL. THIS CAUSED THE TRAILER TO BE UNDER SOME TORQUE. WHEN UNIT 246 WAS PULLED OUT FROM UNDER THE TRAILER, THE INDUCED TORQUE, COMBINED WITH THE WEIGHT OF THE LOAD, CAUSED THE LANDING GEAR TO COLLAPSE ALLOWING THE FRONT OF THE TRAILER TO FALL TO THE HIGHWAY. AS THE LANDING GEAR COLLAPSED AND THE TRAILER FELL, A LANDING GEAR BRACE WAS DRIVEN THROUGH THE BOTTOM OF THE TANK, ALLOWING THE LEAKAGE OF CRUDE OIL.

column168: PACKAGE HAD INNER PLASTIC BOTTLES WHICH ON BOTTLE HAD LEAKED AROUND THE TOP. REPORTING INFORMATION WAS NOT CLEAR ENOUGH TO DETERMINE IF TOPS WERE LOOSE OR DEFECTIVE. CONTENTS WERE CLEANED UP AND PLACED INSIDE A SALVAGE DRUM FOR DISPOSAL.
column172: Plastic bottle, capacity 2 gallons or less

column168: REWRAP AREA HAD BEGAN TO REWRAP THIS SHIPMENT BUT CEASED WHEN A STRONG CHEMICAL ODOR WAS NOTICED. SPILLED LIQUID TURNED LITMUS PAPER DARK RED AND BUBBLED BAKING SODA. AN MSDS AND A TELEPHONE CONVERSATION WITH THE SHIPPER (MR. M. WAXMAN) CONFIRMED THE MATERIAL WAS CORROSIVE (CONTAINS HYDROCHLORIC ACID). THE FAA WAS NOTIFIED AND INVESTIGATED.

A BOX CONTAINING A 20 OZ PLASTIC BOTTLE OF A STARBRIGHT MILDEW STAIN REMOVER WAS DISCOVERED LEAKING. THE MATERIAL SAFETY DATA SHEET (MSDS) INDICATED THIS MATERIAL SHOULD HAVE BEEN SHIPPED AS: CORROSIVE LIQUID N.O.S., CLASS 8, UN1760. FAA WAS NOTIFIED AND INVESTIGATED THE SHIPMENT.

SHIPMENT WAS LEAKING ON THE SORT BELT AND REMOVED. UPON INSPECTION, IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT AN AEROSOL CAN OF SPRAY PAINT HAD COMPLETELY DISCHARGED INSIDE THE BOX. APPARENTLY METAL PIECES INSIDE THE PACKAGE KNOCKED THE VALVE OFF, CAUSING RELEASE OF CONTENTS. THIS PACKAGE WAS NOT MARKED, LABLELLED, OR DECLARED AS A DANGEROUS GOODS SHIPMENT. THE FAA WAS NOTIFIED FOR INSPECTION.

WORE PPE, USED DECISION TREE, REFERENCED CORROSIVE LIQUID RESPONSE SHEET. DID PH TEST. ALL SPILL GENERATE WASTE PROCESSED. SHIPPER PUT PAINT AND CORROSIVE MATERIAL IN SAME BOX AND LABELED BOX AS FLAMMABLE LIQUID ONLY.

column62: Corrosion - Exterior; Loose Closure, Component, or Device
column168: WET PACKAGE WAS DISCOVERED IN THE UNLOAD.

THE PACKAGE WAS DISCOVERED LEAKING IN THE PRIMARY SORT. ONE OF TWO PLASTIC CONTAINERS WAS LEAKING. THE UNDAMAGED CONTAINER WAS REPACKAGED AND RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER. THE DAMAGED CARTON AND THE DAMAGED PLASTIC CONTAINER WERE DISPOSED OF FOLLOWING HAZARDOUS MATERIAL DISPOSAL PROCEDURES.

BRICE FORD, SORTER, NOTICED A LEAKING PACKAGE AFTER PLACING IT ON THE BELT. BRICE LEFT THE AREA IMMEDIATELY AND NOTIFIED JAKE RESSLER, SUPERVISOR. JAKE SECURED THE AREA AND NOTIFIED JEFF COUNTRYMAN, DESIGNATED RESPONDER, JEFF USED GOGGLES, GLOVES, BOOTS, AND APRON TO RESPOND TO THE LEAKING PACKAGE. JEFF USED DECISION TREE TO IDENTIFY THE MATERIAL AND USED RESPONSE SHEETS TO ASSIST IN THE CLEAN UP. AFTER RESPONDING TO SPILL JEFF USED WATER FOR 15 MINUTES TO DECONTAMINATE PPE.
PACKAGE FOUND ON PACKAGE CAR LEAKING. BROUGHT BACK TO BUILDING. PUT THROUGH THE DMP AREA DISPOSAL. NOT ENOUGH INNER PACK. POSSIBLE LOOSE CAPS.

THE PACKAGE WAS DISCOVERED BY SADIE MANN. SHE IMMEDIATELY STOPPED BELT AND NOTIFIED SUPERVISOR DARREN CAVALIER. THE AREA AROUND THE SPILL WAS SECURED AND THE PACKAGE WAS PLACED IN A DMP BAG AND PROCESSED THROUGH THE DMP. THE CAUSE OF THE SPILL WAS IMPROPER PACKAGING. THE INNER CONTAINER WAS PLACED IN THE USED CARTON UPSIDE DOWN. THE CAP WAS LOOSE THUS CAUSING LEAKAGE. THE SPILL WAS CLEANED UP SUCCESSFULLY.

column42: AEROSOLS, FLAMMABLE, (EACH NOT EXCEEDING 1 L CAPACITY)
column168: ADDITIONAL COMMENTS; ON JUNE 16, 1995 AT 02:14 AM, A SPILL WAS REPORTED BY MIKE BANKS, SORT SUPERVISOR AT ABX AIR, INC. SPILL TECHNICIANS, JEFF MCLAUGHLIN AND CAROLYN CORDREY RESPONDED. UPON ARRIVAL, THEY NOTICED A WET AREA OF THE FIBREBOARD BOX. AFTER FURTHER INVESTIGATION OF THE INNER CONTENTS, THEY DISCOVERED SEVERAL REGULATED HAZARDOUS MATERIALS. ITEMS MARKED AS; "AEROSOLS FLAMMABLE", "2.1", "UN1950", "FLAMMABLE SOLIDS", "4.1" "UN1325", AND "POISONOUS SOLID, NOS", "6.1", "UN2811". THE ONLY LEAKING MATERIAL WAS A METAL RECEPTACLE OF WD-40. THE PLASTIC PROTECTIVE CLOSURE HAD COME OFF. THERE WAS NO POSITIVE MEANS TO SECURE THE PROTECTIVE CLOSURE THIS BOX ALSO CONTAINED OTHER MISC. NON-HAZARDOUS MATERIALS. THE ONLY CUSHIONING MATERIAL WAS ONE PIECE OF BUBBLE WRAP. THE ONLY THEORY WE HAVE FOR THIS SHIPMENT LEAKING IS POSSIBLE RUBBING AND ABRASING OF THE CONTENTS OF THE BOX. THERE WAS NO INDICATION THAT THIS WAS A REGULATED MATERIAL. THERE WERE NO MARKINGS OR LABELS ON THE BOX AND PROPER CERTIFICATION DID NOT ACCOMPANY THIS SHIPMENT. THE FIBREBOARD BOX IS BEING HELD AT ILN IN A SECURITY CAGE UNDER LOCK AND KEY PENDING A F.A.A. INVESTIGATION.

UPRR HARRIMAN DISPATCH REPORTED THAT TANK CAR UTLX 99074 WAS LEAKING AT THE ROCK TENN INDUSTRIES, STERRITT, TX.  ROCK TENN SUPERVISOR SMELLED AMMONIA AND CALLED THE WAXAHACHIE FIRE DEPT. THE FIRE DEPT. COULD NOT FIND A PROBLEM BUT NOTIFIED UPRR DISPATCH.  UPRR CTS MANAGER ARLA ROQUET RESPONDED TO THE SCENE.  THE CAR HAD BEEN SET TO THE ROCK TENN SPUR TRACK TO AWAIT BEING SPOTTED AT LAROCHE INDUSTRIES (2 INDUSTRIES AWAY) ON MONDAY, 6/5/95, AFTERNOON.  THE DOCK DOORS OF ROCK TENN WERE IMMEDIATELY ADJACENT TO THE CAR.  INSPECTION OF THE CAR FOUND THAT THE LIQUID BALL VALVE HANDLE WAS LEAKING AT THE STEM.  WHEN THE PRESSURE WAS TAKEN AT THE SAMPLE LINE, THE SAMPLE LINE HANDLE ALSO STARTED TO LEAK.  GORTEX GASKET MATERIAL WAS PACKED BETWEEN THE VALVE BODY AND THE VALVE HANDLE.  THIS REDUCED, BUT DID NOT ELIMINATE, THE PROBLEM.  THE SAMPLE IN HANDLE LEAK STOPPED WHEN CLOSED.  MS. ROQUET CONTACTED UPRR MTO GENE GARRETT TO ARRANGE FOR THE CAR TO BE SPOTTED TO LAROCHE IMMEDIATELY.  LAROCHE, STERRETT PLANT (214) 299-5349, ARRANGED FOR THE CAR TO BE OFFLOADED AS SOON AS SPOTTED.  LAROCHE ALSO STATED THEY WOULD BAD-ORDER THE CAR AND "HOME SHOP" FOR REPAIRS WHEN UNLOADED.  THE CAR WAS SPOTTED AT 1400 HRS., 6/4/95.  JEFF, CHEMTREC, WAS NOTIFIED AT 0445 HRS., 6/4/95.

SPECIAL AGENT HAZMAT, TOM SMITH WAS NOTIFIED THAT TANK CAR WAS LEAKING FROM THE PROTECTIVE COVER ON THE TOP OF THE TANK CAR.  PRODUCT RAN PART WAY DOWN THE SIDE OF THE CAR AND VAPORIZED BEFORE LEAVING THE TANKCAR. UPON INSPECTION I FOUND PRODUCT LEAKING FROM THE LIQUID LINE FLANGE BELOW THE VALVE.  ATTEMPTS TO TIGHTEN THE BOLTS ON THE FLANGE MET WITH EXTREME RESISTANCE AND ONE BOLT AND NUT TURNED TOGETHER.  CONTACT WAS MADE WITH THE SHIPPER THROUGH CHEMTREC AND SHIPPER REPRESENTATIVES ARRIVED AND MADE REPAIRS TO THE CAR.  THE CAR WAS WATCHED FOR 12 HOURS WITH NO FURTHER LEAKS DETECTED.  THE CAR WAS THEN RELEASED FOR CONTINUED MOVEMENT.

WHILE CONDUCTING REGULATORY COMPLIANCE INSPECTIONS AT NORTH PLATTE, IN COMPANY WITH MGR. C.T.S. DEAN COOPER, TANK CAR PLMX035338, RESIDUE ANYDROUS AMMONIA WAS NOTED WITH VAPOR LEAK AT THE PACKING GLAND NUT. PACKING GLAND NUT TIGHTENED SUFFICIENT TO STOP THE LEAK.  CHEMTREC WAS NOTIFIED AS WAS THE SHIPPER, SPEAKING WITH MGR. B.D. EYRING.

DEAN C. COOPER, MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS NOTIFIED BY MIKE SCOGGINS, MANAGER, TRAIN OPERATIONS, YERMO, CALIFORNIA, WHO STATED THE MECHANICAL DEPARTMENT PERSONNEL HAD LOCATED A TANK CAR IN THE CENTER OF YARD TRACK C-3, THAT WAS LEAKING PRODUCT FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLET, AND FORMING A LARGE POOL UNDERNEATH THE RAILCAR.  THE CAR WAS MOVED FROM THE YARD TRACK AND PLACED IN THE RD YARD POCKET TRACK WHERE IT COULD BE ISOLATED PENDING INSPECTION.  ARRANGEMENTS WERE MADE WITH ENVIRONMENTAL TECHNOLOGIES TO RESPOND PERSONNEL AND EQUIPMENT OUT OF LAS VEGAS, ALONG WITH ROBERT JONES, SPECIAL AGENT HAZARDOUS MATERIALS.  THE YARD FORCES AT YERMO ALSO MADE NOTIFICATION TO THE LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT.  A CONTAINMENT DIKE WAS FORMED AROUND THE AREA OF THE TANK CAR BY UTILIZING A BACK HOE REQUISITIONED FROM A CONTRACTOR WORKING IN THE YARD.  THE FIRE DEPARTMENT REQUIRED THE WEST END OF THE YARD BE CLOSED TO SWITCHING OPERATIONS DUE TO THE HEAVY WIND CONDITIONS CARRYING VAPORS FROM THE PRODUCT ACROSS THE YARD, AS WELL AS CONCERN OVER THE TANK CAR INTEGRITY FAILING.  THE CAR WAS LEAKING AROUND THE BOTTOM OUTLET FLANGE WHERE THE VALVE ATTACHES. ATTEMPTS TO TIGHTEN THE BOLTS THAT ATTACH THE VALVE TO THE BOTTOM OUTLET HAD SOME EFFECT IN SLOWING THE DRIP, WHICH WAS ESTIMATED AT 1/2 GALLON PER MINUTE. PLACING PUTTY AROUND THE FLANGE FURTHER REDUCED THE LEAK, HOWEVER, THE PRODUCT STARTED DRIPPING FROM THREE OTHER LOCATIONS AT THE BOTTOM OF THE TANK CAR SHELL.  HIGHWAY TANK TRUCKS WERE BROUGHT IN AND UTLIZED TO TRANSFER THE PRODUCT FROM THE TANK CAR.  ALL OF THE TRANSFERRED PRODUCT WAS TRANSPORTED TO THE FMC PLANT LOCATED IN THE CITY OF INDUSTRY WHERE IT WAS TRANSFERED BACK INTO A TANK CAR, AND CURRENTLY ON HOLD PENDING A BUYER FOR THE PRODUCT.  THE AREA WHERE THE TANK CAR SAT IN THE YARD, AS WELL AS THE AREA AROUND THE POCKET TRACK, WAS COVERED WITH AGRICULTURAL LIME AND WATERED TO NEUTRALIZE THE SITES.  SITE REMEDIATION WILL BE ADDRESSED WITH THE REGIONAL WATER QUALITY CONTROL BOARD FOR SAN BERNARDINO COUNTY.  THE TANK CAR WAS STENCILED PURSUANT TO SECTION 174.50 OF 49 CFR, AND SCHEDULED FOR MOVEMENT TO THE SHIPPER FOR INSPECTION AND TESTING.  NOTIFICATIONS WERE MADE THE CHEMTREC, CALIFORNIA OFFICE OF EMERGENCY SERVICES, COUNTY OF SAN BERNARDINO DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL HEALTH SERVICES, LA HONTAN WATER QUALITY CONTROL BOARD, AND THE SHIPPER.

column168: MANAGERS, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, D.A. LOW AND F.H. LERCH, WHILE CONDUCTING A TANKCAR AUDIT, NORTH PLATTE, NOTED EXCEPTIONS TO TANK CAR GATX 52470.  INSPECTION REVEALED THAT SECO 100# FRANGIBLE DISC, HAD RUPTURED. TANK CAR EQUIPPED WITH GATX MANWAY MOUNTED VENT.  ALSO, NOTED 2 INCH EDUCTION NOZZLE FLANGE HAD 3 OUT OF 4 BOLTS WITH NUTS LOOSE AND 1 OUT OF 4 BOLTS WAS MISSING 1 NUT.  FURTHER, EDUCTION PIPE HAD PIPE CAP CROSS THREADED.  REPLACED RUPTURED FRANGIBLE DISC, WITH CDC #100 DISC AND SECURED EDUCTION NOZZLE FLANGE, WHICH STOPPED LEAK.  MILAZZO, CHEMTREC FILE #36452 AND MS. PAT PRINE, U.S. AGRI CHEMICALS, WERE NOTIFIED OF EXCEPTIONS.

TANK CAR OBSERVED BY YARD PERSONNEL AT UNION PACIFIC RAILYARD AT ALEXANDRIA, LOUISIANA TO BE LEAKING A SMALL AMOUNT OF LIQUID FROM THE TOP OF THE CAR.  THE CAR WAS SET OUT AND ISOLATED WITH OUT INCIDENT.  UPRR SPECIAL AGENT B. G. BAREFIELD WAS NOTIFIED AND IN TURN NOTIFIED THE FOLLOWING, UPRR MANAGER OF MECHANICAL MAINTENANCE CLESS BODILY, UPRR REGIONAL MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORATION SAFETY T.M. ROBINSON,  CHEMTREC, LOUISIANA STATE POLICE, ALEXANDRIA 911 CENTER AND THE LOUISIANA DEPT OF ENVIRONMENTAL QUALITY.  ROBINSON RESPONDED TO THE SCENE AND INSPECTED THE CAR.  THIS INSPECTION REVEALED THAT THE MANWAY COVER DID NOT HAVE A GASKET.  ROBINSON SPOKE WITH MR. THURMAN BELL OF GEORGIA GULF AND INFORMED HIM OF THE MISSING GASKET.  BELL REQUESTED THAT ROBINSON INSTALL A NEW GASKET.  THIS WAS DONE AND THE CAR WAS SECURED FOR MOVEMENT AT ABOUT 1610 HOURS.  MR. BOBBY LAMBRIGHT OF THE LA-DEQ RESPONDED TO THE SCENE AND OBSERVED THAT ALL OF THE SPILLAGE EVAPORATED OFF OF THE TOP OF CAR.  NO FURTHER REMEDIATION WAS NEEDED.

column62: Improper Preparation for Transportation; Abrasion; Impact with Sharp or Protruding Object (e.g., nails); Inadequate Blocking and Bracing
column168: S/A, BALANCE RECEIVED A REPORT FROM BONNIE AT THE UPMF THAT CONTAINER KLTU 110119 WAS FOUND TO BE LEAKING.  THE CONTAINER WAS OPENED AND DUE TO THE LOADING METHOD MORGAN ENVIRONMENTAL WAS CONTACTED TO ASSIST.  THREE 2X4'S WERE USED AS CROSS BRACING IN THE DOOR OF THE CONTAINER.  THE LEAK WAS CONTAINED ON SUNDAY.  ON MONDAY THE DRUMS WERE REMOVED FROM THE CONTAINER. TWENTY DRUMS WERE FOUND TO BE LEAKING.  THE CROWN ON THE BOTTOM OF THE DRUMS WERE FOUND TO BE LEAKING.  THE CROWN ON THE BOTTOM OF THE DRUMS HAD WORN THROUGH CAUSING THEM TO LEAK.  ALSO FOUND WERE TWO SCREWS PROTRUDING FROM THE FLOOR.  ALL OF THE DRUMS WERE OVERPACKED AND PLACED INTO A SECOND CONTAINER.  THE UNDAMAGED DRUMS WERE ALSO PLACED IN THE CONTAINER. CONTACT HAD BEEN MADE WITH JOHN LOPEZ OF K-LINE.  HE PROVIDED THE SECOND CONTAINER AND AGREED TO ACCEPT CHARGED FOR THE CLEAN-UP.  DENNIS BIGGS WITH THE CA PUC IS ALSO CONDUCTING AND INVESTIGATION INTO THE CAUSE.  OES NUMBER 008786.

column168: UPRR MOCKINGBIRD YARDMASTER REPORTED THAT TANK CAR GATX23993 WAS LEAKING PRODUCT FROM THE TOP WHEN THE CAR WAS MOVED.  IT HAD BEEN SENT TO TRACK , MOCKINGBIRD YARD.  UPRR CTS MANAGER ARLA ROQUET RESPONDED TO THE SCENE AND FOUND THE BS&B FLANGIBLE DISC HAD BURST.  IT WAS REPLACED WITH A LIKE KIND.  THE CAR EXTERIOR WAS WASHING OFF AND CAR WAS RELEASED FOR AT 1400, DATE.  JOE DEBMAN, CHEMTREC, WAS NOTIFIED.  REPORT #36736.  BOB SCHOLLAERT, OCCIDENTAL (713) 476-2220, WAS ADVISED.

ON 062695 AT APPROXIMATELY 1AM, REEDER RECEIVED A CALL FROM MTO SKINNER THAT THE ABOVE CAR HAD BEEN DISCOVERED LEAKING BY THE SWITCH CREW.  THEY REPORTED IT WAS ALSO STINKING.  REEDER INTERVIEWED THE CREW TO FIND OUT WHAT THEY HAD SEEN.  THEY SAID THE CAR WAS LEAKING FROM THE TOP.  REEDER ALSO CONTACTED CHEMTREC AND THE SHIPPER FOR PRODUCT INFORMATION AND PERSONAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT INFORMATION.  SPECIAL AGENT MILLS ACCOMPANIED REEDER TO EQUIPMENT INFORMATION.  SPECIAL AGENT MILLS TO THE TOP OPERATED BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE.  THE CAP WAS REMOVED AND THE PACKING NUT FOUND LOOSE.  THERE WAS A SEAL ON THE CAP, HOWEVER, IT WAS NOT READABLE. THE PACKING NUT WAS FROZEN AND WOULD NOT TURN. GORE TEX WAS FORCED INTO THE OPENING TO SEAL IT AND HOPEFULLY PREVENT FURTHER SPILLAGE. AS THE PACKAGE WAS BEING STAGED FOR LOADING THE FEDEX EMPLOYEE, FERNANDO NINO PICKED UP THE DEWER AND FELT LIQUID MOVING WITHIN THE DEWAR. AS DRY "VAPOR" DEWARS ARE NO LONGER REGULATED, THIS SEEMED OUT OF THE  ORDINARY. FERNANDO TIPPED THE DEWAR TO A 90 DEGREE ANGLE AND WATCHED LIQUID NITROGEN SPILL OUT OF THE DEWAR. AS SUCH, THIS DEWAR IS "WET" AND THEREFORE REGULATED. THE F.A.A. HAS INSPECTED THE SHIPMENT, RELEASED IT AND THE RECIPIENT PICKED IT UP. THE SHIPPER HAS BEEN NOTIFIED.
