column168: A CLEAN ENVIRONMENT RECEIVED A CALL AT 10:30 A.M. FROM TAMMY WITH SCHNEIDER NATIONAL THAT THEY HAD A TRUCK LOADED WITH 80 FIFTY FIVE GALLON DRUMS LEAKING FROM THE TRAILER AT THE LOVE'S COUNTRY STORE IN OKLAHOMA CITY ON I-40 AND MORGAN ROAD. THE DRUMS CONTAINED A RESIN SOLUTION THAT WAS HIGHLY FLAMMABLE. THE A CLEAN ENVIRONMENT MOBILIZED THE HAZ-MAT TRUCK ON ITS WAY TO OKLAHOMA CITY IMMEDIATELY. CONTACTED PERSONNEL THAT WERE IN THE CITY ALREADY AND HAD THEM GO TO THE SITE AND SECURE THE TRAILER AND MAKE SURE THAT ALL PERSONS IN AND AROUND THE FACILITY STAYED CLEAR OF THE INCIDENT. THE SPREAD ABSORBENT AROUND ON THE PRODUCT THAT HAD LEAKED OUT OF THE TRAILER AND PUT UP SAFETY CONES. LONNIE EDWARDS, PROJECT COORDINATOR ARRIVED ON THE SCENE IN OKLAHOMA CITY, AND CHECKED OUT THE SITUATION. RECEIVED PERMISSION FROM RYAN, THE LOVE'S COUNTRY STORE MANAGER TO STAGE THE TRAILER ON THEIR PROPERTY FOR THE CLEANUP OPERATION. JEFFDUNKIN, OPERATIONS MANAGER FOR A CLEAN ENVIRONMENT ARRIVED ON THE SCENE WITH THE HAZ-MAT TRUCK. THE SCHNEIDER TRAILER WAS MOVED TO THE SOUTH SIDE OF THE LOVE'S FACILITY. A SHEET OF 6 MIL PLASTIC WAS PLACED ON THE GROUND UNDER THE TRAILER TO KEEP THE PRODUCT FROM CONTAMINATING THE PAVEMENT ANY FURTHER. LONNIE EDWARDS, PROJECT COORDINATOR MADE THE ENTRY INTO THE TRAILER TO INSPECT THE SITUATION. UPON THE INSPECTION OF THE INSIDE OF THE TRAILER IT WAS NOTED THAT THE LOAD HAS NEVER SHIFTED FROM THE ORGINAL POSITION. ALL CONTAINERS ARE LEAKING FROM EITHER A 2" DRUM BUNG, 3/4 VENT, SIDE RING DAMAGE, ETC.

column58: Auxiliary Valve; Bottom Outlet Valve; Piping or Fittings
column168: WHILE HEATING TANK CAR GATX 58579, SULPHUR, MOLTEN, IN PREPARATION FOR FILED TRANSFER INTO TANK CAR GATX 300805, A LEAK WAS DISCOVERED AT THE GFOUR (4) BOLTS FLANGE LOCATED EXTERNAL TO THE INTERNAL BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE ON TANK CAR.  TANK CAR GATX 59579 HAD BEEN INVOLVED IN A DERAILMENT WHICH RESULTED IN IMPACT WITH GROUND CAUSING DAMAGE TO THREADED BOTTOM OUTLET NOZZLE AND CAP, AND POTENTIAL DAMAGE TO BOLTED FLANGE AND INTERNAL BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE; HOWEVER, NO DAMAGE OR EVIDENCE OF LEAKAGE WAS VISIBLE TO FLANGE/VALVE.  BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE OPERATING HANDLE WAS MISSING.  A STEEL PLATE WITH TWO(2) INCH NIPPLE WITH BALL VALVE HAD BEEN WELDED ON NOZZLE FOR ADDITIONAL PROTECTION. WHEN LEAK WAS DISCOVERED, HEATING PROCESS WAS TERMINATED, AREA OS BOTTOM OUTLET WAS COOLED TO SOLIDIFY PRODUCT, SO REPAIRS COULD BE MADE.  UNION PACIFIC REGIONAL MANAGER DEAN L. WHITELEY AND MANAGER FRANK H. LERCH, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY DEPARTMENT, CLEANED UP SOLIDIFIED PRODUCT WHICH WAS DISPOSED OF IN LOCAL LANDFILL UNDER AUTHORITY OF JIM BOROVICH, NEBRASKA DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL QUALITY, CASE #062795-JB-1010.  HERSHEL STAFFORD, EXXON, BATON ROUGE, LA. WAS FURNISHED DETAILS OF THIS SPILL.

column62: Improper Preparation for Transportation; Inadequate Blocking and Bracing; Too Much Weight on Package
column168: DEAN C COOPER, MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS NOTIFIED BY APL EMPLOYEES STATIONED IN THE UNION PACIFIC RAILROAD INTERMODAL FACILITY, LOS ANGELES, THAT A FORTY FOOT CONTAINER HAD BEEN NOTED LEAKING WHILE IT WAS BEING GROUNDED.  THE CONTAINER ARRIVED LOS ANGELES AT 1835 HOURS, FRIDAY, JUNE 23, 1995 ON THE CHLAZ-20, AND GROUNDED AT 1935 HOURS.  THE CONTAINER WAS SET TO TRAILER STROAGE LOT #16 WHERE IT WAS ISOLATD PENDEING INSPECTION .  INSPECTION DEVELOPED THE CONTAINER WAS LEAKING PRODUCT THROUGH THE FLOORING, NEAR THE CENTER OF THE CONTAINER.  WAYBILL INFORMATION SHOWED 8 PALLETS OF ADHESIVE MATERIALS AND A SINGLE CONTAINER OF CORROSIVE MATERIAL. UPON OPENING THE REAR DOORS, DEVELOPED THE CONTENTS TO BE MIXED FREIGHT.  THERE WERE FOUR 2X4S ACROSS THE DOORWAY IN AN "X" PATTERN, WHICH WAS THE ONLY ATTEMPT AT BLOCKING AND BRACING.  AN ATTEMPT WAS MADE TO LOCATE THE SOURCE OF THE LEAK, HOWEVER, DUE TO THE MANNER OF LOADING UTILIZED IN PLACING THE LOOSE CARTONS, IT WAS IMPOSSIBLE TO LOCATE WHERE OR WHAT WAS LEAKING.  IN AN ATTEMPT TO KEEP THE TRANSLOADING COST AT A MINIMUM, AND ALSO, ANZDL COULD NOT PROVIDE AN MSDS FOR THE CORROSIVE AND FLAMMABLE LIQUIDS, THE CONTAINER REMAINED ISOLATED UNTIL MONDAY MORNING, WHEN THE APPROPRIATE INFORMATION COULD BE OBTAINED. ON MONDAY MORNING, A PORTION OF THE LADING WAS REMOVED TO LOCATE THE PAILS OF ADHESIVE.  ONCE LOCATED, THE MANUFACTURER WAS CONTACTED AND PROVIDED AN MSDS ON THE BOTH OF THE COMMODITIES THAT WERE KNOWN TO BE IN THE CONTAINER.  THE FIRST PALLET OF MATERIAL, A SOLVENT PRIMER, KNOWN AS A602 -B, WAS LOCATED SEVERAL FEET IN FROM THE REAR DOOR ON THE LEFT SIDE OF THE CONTAINER.  THE PALLET CONTAINED 24 5-GALLON PAILS, DOUBLE STACKED ON THE PALLET, BANDED, AND STRETCH WRAPPED.  THE PALLET WAS ON THE FLOOR OF THE CONTAINER WITH NUMEROUS HEAVY CARTONS OF FREIGHT STACKED ON TOP THE PAILS. ONE PAIL FROM THE TOP LAYER ON THE PALLET WAS SLIGHTLY CRUSHED, CAUSING THE SIDE OF THEMETALPAIL TO CRIMP AT THE WIRE CARRY HANDLE ATTACHMENT, THUS ALLOWING THE PRODUCT TO SEEP DOWN THE SIDE OF THE PAIL AND POOL ON THE PALLET.  THEIS PAIL WAS REMOVED AND PLACED INTO AN OVERPACK FOR CONTAINMENT. FURTHER INTO THE CONTAINER, SEVERAL OTHER PALLETS OF THE SAME PRODUCT WERE LOCATED ON THE FLOOR LEVEL, WHICH HAD A LARGE REFRIGERATION UNIT PLACED ON TOP OF THE PAILS.  THIS UNIT WAS ESTIMATED TO WEIGH IN EXCESS OF 2500 POUNDS.  NUMEROUS PAILS ON THE UPPER STACK WERE CRUSHED FORM THE WEIGHT OF THIS UNIT BEING PLACED ON TOP OF THEM.  ALL OF THE LEAKING PAILS WERE PLACED N TO AN OVERPACK FOR CONTAINMENT.  A TOTAL OF 11 PAILS WERE LOCATED THAT HAD PRODUCT LEAKING DUE TO DAMAGE SUSTAINED FORM VERY HEAVY PIECES OF FREIGHT BEING PLACED ON TOP OF THEM.  ALL WERE PLACED INTO OVERPACKS.  AN ADDITIONAL 4 5-GALLON PAILS OF THE SAME PRODUCT WERE LOCATED THAT HAD SUFFICIENT DAMAGE TO WARRANT BEING PLACED IN TO OVERPACKS TO PRECLUDE A FUTURE RELEASE OF PRODUCT.  THE REMAINING PAILS EWRE REGROUPED AND PREPARED FOR RELOADING INTO CON

WHILE UNLOADING ONE CARTON FELL OVER AND THE PLASTIC CAPS ON THE GLASS JUGS BROKE SPILLING SOME OF THE LIQUID.  SMITH ENVIRONMENTAL WILL HANDLE THE CLEANUP AND DISPOSAL.  STATEMENT FROM BOB WEIGAND, REGIONAL SAFETY SUPERIVSOR, ROCKY MOUNTAIN.

column42: BATTERIES, WET, FILLED WITH ACID, ELECTRIC STORAGE
column168: BATTERIES DOUBLE STACKED ON PALLET AND 7 BATTERIES FELL OVER, SPILLING ACID ON EMPLOYEE.  MEDICAL ATTENTION WAS GIVEN FOR POSSIBLE ACID BURNS. STATEMENT FROM BOB WEIGAND, REGIONAL SAFETY SUPERVISOR, ROCKY MOUNTAIN.

AS THE BOX WAS BEING SORTED IT WAS DROPPED. THE TWO INNER CYLINDERS CAME OUT OF THE BOX. AS THERE WERE NO MARKINGS, LABELING, SHIPPING PAPERS OR OTHER INDICATORS TO LEAD US TO BELIEVE IT WAS A DANGEROUS GOODS, WE ARE HOLDING IT FOR AN FAA INSPECTION. NUMEROUS ATTEMPTS TO REACH THE SHIPPER HAVE BEEN UNSUCCESSFUL.
WORE PPE, USED DECISION TREE, REFERENCED FLAMMABLE LIUQID RESPONSE SHEET. USED SOLUSORB TO NEUTRALIZE LIQUID.  ALL SPILL GENERATED WAS PROCESSED THROUGH DMP.
OUTSIDE CARTON LOOKED WET.  PUT ON PPE TO CHECK PACKAGE NO SPILLAGE ON BELTS, CARDBOARD SOAKED UP OR WAS EVAPORATED.  CALLED SHIPPER TO PICK UP; SHIPPER AGREED.

column168: AT APPROXIMATELY 1130 HOURS ON JUNE 28, 1995, A CONRAIL YARD CREW WORKING AT CONWAY YARD REPORTED OBSERVING TANK CAR SCMX 2543 WITH A SMALL LEAK FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLET CAP.  A BUCKET WAS PLACED UNDER THE BOTTOM OUTLET WHERE THE DRIP WAS OCCURRING.  THE LEAKAGE WAS ESTIMATED AT APPROXIMATELY ONE DROP EVERY 20 SECONDS, PRODUCT EVAPORATED BEFORE ANY MEASURABLE AMOUNT COLLECTED. MR TOM GIMBUS OF GREAT LAKES TERMINAL & TRANSPORT CORP. RESPONDED TO CONWAY YARD AND REMOVED THE BOTTOM OUTLET CAP AND DISCOVERED THE BOTTOM OUTLET CAP GASKET MISSING.  MR GIMBUS REPLACED THE GASKET AND SECURED THE OUTLET CAP TO THE BOTTOM OUTLET.  TANK CAR SECURED AND FORWARDED TO DESTINATION ON JUNE 28, 1995.

SEAL BNIG 232313 WAS REMOVED TO OPEN THE COVER PLATE FOR INSPECTION, WHICH DEVELOPED THE SOURCE OF THE LEAK TO BE FROM THE GAUGING ROD ASSEMBLEY AT THE PACKING GLAND NUT.
